<section xml:id="section-linear-equations-and-inequalities">
  <title>Linear Equations and Inequalities</title>

  <introduction>
    <p>
      Linear equations and inequalities are relatively straightforward to solve. There are a few
      standard steps to learn, and then isolating the variable in a linear equation becomes second
      nature.
    </p>

    <!-- <figure>
      <caption>Alternative Video Lessons</caption>
      <video youtubeplaylist="PLmuZCPhWPt-f7ezMxAmmOJqEHiU6BOLTH" />
    </figure> -->
  </introduction>

  <subsection>
    <title>Solving Two-Step Equations</title>                                                                 <idx><h>Equation(s)</h><h>using both addition and multiplication properties</h></idx>
    <example xml:id="example-two-step-equation">
      <p>
        A water tank can hold up to <m>140</m> gallons of water, but it starts with only <m>5</m>
        gallons. A tap is opened, pouring <m>15</m> gallons of water into the tank every minute.
        How long will it take to fill the tank?
      </p>
      <p>
        This is a scenario describing a <q>rate</q>. We can explore what is happening with a table.
        Tables can reveal patterns that help understand what is happening better.
      </p>

      <tabular>
        <col halign="center" />
        <col halign="left"/>
        <row bottom="medium">
          <cell>
            <line>Time Tap Running</line>
            <line>(in Minutes)</line>
          </cell>
          <cell>
            <line>Water in Tank</line>
            <line>(in Gallons)</line>
          </cell>
        </row>
        <row>
          <cell><m>0</m></cell>
          <cell><m>\phantom{0}5</m></cell>
        </row>
        <row>
          <cell><m>1</m></cell>
          <cell><m>20</m></cell>
        </row>
        <row>
          <cell><m>2</m></cell>
          <cell><m>35</m></cell>
        </row>
        <row>
          <cell><m>3</m></cell>
          <cell><m>50</m></cell>
        </row>
        <row>
          <cell><m>4</m></cell>
          <cell><m>65</m></cell>
        </row>
        <row>
          <cell><m>\vdots</m></cell>
          <cell><m>\phantom{0}\vdots</m></cell>
        </row>
      </tabular>

      <p>
        Each additional minute of time gives us <m>15</m> more gallons of water. So after <m>t</m>
        minutes, we've added <m>15t</m> gallons of water to the <m>5</m> gallons that we started
        with. And after <m>t</m> minutes, we have <m>15t+5</m> gallons total. To find when the tank
        will be full with <m>140</m> gallons, we can write the equation
        <md>
          15t+5=140
        </md>
      </p>

      <p>
        We follow a simple strategy to solve this equation. First we want to isolate the variable
        term <m>15t</m>. How to do that? We need to separate it from the <q><m>5</m></q> term. We
        can do this in a valid way using the
        <xref ref="fact-properties-of-equivalent-equations" text="custom">subtraction property of equality</xref>,
        subtracting <m>5</m> from each side of the equation.
        <md>
          <mrow>15t+5\amp=140</mrow>
          <mrow>15t+5\subtractright{5}\amp=140\subtractright{5}</mrow>
          <mrow>15t\amp=135</mrow>
        </md>
        And now that the variable term <m>15t</m> is isolated, we can separate the <m>t</m> from the
        <m>15</m> using the
        <xref ref="fact-properties-of-equivalent-equations" text="custom">division property of equality</xref>,
        dividing by <m>15</m> on each side.
        <md>
          <mrow>\divideunder{15t}{15}\amp=\divideunder{135}{15}</mrow>
          <mrow>t\amp=9</mrow>
        </md>
        We should check this possible solution by substituting <m>9</m> in for <m>t</m> in the
        original equation:
        <md>
          <mrow>15t+5\amp=140</mrow>
          <mrow>15(\substitute{9})+5\amp\wonder{=}140</mrow>
          <mrow>135+5\amp\confirm{=}140</mrow>
        </md>
        And the solution <m>9</m> is verified.
      </p>

      <p>
        This problem had <em>context</em>. It was not simply solving an equation. It came with a
        story about a tank filling with water. So we should report a conclusion that uses that
        context. Something like
      </p>
      <blockquote>
        <p>
          <q>The tank will be full after <m>9</m> minutes.</q>
        </p>
      </blockquote>
    </example>

    <p>
      In solving the equation in <xref ref="example-two-step-equation"/>, we first isolated the
      variable expression <m>15t</m> and then eliminated the coefficient <m>15</m> by dividing each
      side of the equation by <m>15</m>. These two steps are the heart of our strategy to solving
      linear equations in general. Try these two steps in the following exercise.
    </p>

    <exercise label="solve-two-step">
      <webwork>
        <pg-code>
          Context("FiniteSolutionSets")->variables->are(y => 'Real');
          $solution = Formula("{5}");
        </pg-code>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Solve for <m>y</m> in the equation <m>7-3y=-8</m>.
          </p>
          <p>
            <var name="$solution" width="5"/>
          </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
          <p>
            To solve, we first separate the variable terms and constant terms to different sides of
            the equation. Then we eliminate the variable term's coefficient.
            <md>
              <mrow>7-3y\amp=-8</mrow>
              <mrow>7-3y\subtractright{7}\amp=-8\subtractright{7}</mrow>
              <mrow>-3y\amp=-15</mrow>
              <mrow>\divideunder{-3y}{-3}\amp=\divideunder{-15}{-3}</mrow>
              <mrow>y\amp=5</mrow>
            </md>
            Checking the solution <m>y=5</m>:
            <md>
              <mrow>7-3y\amp=-8</mrow>
              <mrow>7-3(\substitute{5})\amp\wonder{=}-8</mrow>
              <mrow>7-15\amp\confirm{=}-8</mrow>
            </md>
            So the solution to the equation <m>7-3y=-8</m> is <m>5</m> and the solution set is
            <m>\{5\}</m>.
          </p>
        </solution>
      </webwork>
    </exercise>

    <p>
      In <xref ref="section-modeling-with-equations-and-inequalities"/>, there was
      <xref ref="example-savings-pattern"/>. In that example, some background information let us set
      up an equation, but we didn't try to solve it. Now we can try solving it.
    </p>

    <exercise label="savings-pattern">
      <webwork>
        <pg-code>
          $t = NumberWithUnits("8 months");
        </pg-code>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Your savings account starts with <m>\$500</m>. Then each month, there is an automatic
            deposit of <m>\$150</m>. You need <m>\$1700</m> to afford a deposit on a new apartment.
            How long will this take?
          </p>
          <p>
            <var name="$t" width="16"/>
          </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
          <p>
            With any word problem, it is best to clearly define the variable you will use once you
            really understand what the question is asking for. In this case, we let <m>t</m> (for
            time) be the number of months until you have saved up <m>\$1700</m>.
          </p>
          <p>
            To set up an equation, we might start by making a table in order to identify a general
            pattern for the total amount in the savings account after <m>t</m> months.
          </p>
          <tabular>
            <col halign="center" />
            <col halign="left"/>
            <row bottom="medium">
              <cell>
                <line>Time Passed</line>
                <line>(in Months)</line>
              </cell>
              <cell>
                <line>Account Balance</line>
                <line>(in Dollars)</line>
              </cell>
            </row>
            <row>
              <cell><m>0</m></cell>
              <cell><m>500</m></cell>
            </row>
            <row>
              <cell><m>1</m></cell>
              <cell><m>650</m> (<m>150</m> more than <m>500</m>)</cell>
            </row>
            <row>
              <cell><m>2</m></cell>
              <cell><m>800</m> (<m>300</m> more than <m>500</m>)</cell>
            </row>
            <row>
              <cell><m>3</m></cell>
              <cell><m>950</m> (<m>450</m> more than <m>500</m>)</cell>
            </row>
            <row>
              <cell><m>4</m></cell>
              <cell><m>1100</m> (<m>600</m> more than <m>500</m>)</cell>
            </row>
            <row>
              <cell><m>\vdots</m></cell>
              <cell halign="center"><m>\vdots</m></cell>
            </row>
          </tabular>

          <p>
            We find the pattern is that after <m>t</m> months, the total amount saved is
            <m>150t + 500</m>. Using this pattern, we set up the equation
            <md>
              150t + 500 = 1700
            </md>
            to represent when we will have saved up <m>\$1700</m>. To solve this equation, we start
            by subtracting <m>500</m> from each side. Then we can divide each side by <m>150</m>.
            <md>
              <mrow>500+150m\amp=1700</mrow>
              <mrow>500+150m\subtractright{500}\amp=1700\subtractright{500}</mrow>
              <mrow>150m\amp=1200</mrow>
              <mrow>\divideunder{150m}{150}\amp=\divideunder{1200}{150}</mrow>
              <mrow>m\amp=8</mrow>
            </md>
            Checking the solution <m>8</m>:
            <md>
              <mrow>500+150m               \amp         = 1700</mrow>
              <mrow>500+150(\substitute{8})\amp \wonder{=}1700</mrow>
              <mrow>500+1200               \amp\confirm{=}1700</mrow>
            </md>
            So <m>8</m> is the solution, and it checks out. This means it will take <m>8</m> months
            for the account balance to reach <m>\$1700</m>.
          </p>
        </solution>
      </webwork>
    </exercise>
  </subsection>

  <subsection>
    <title>Solving Multistep Linear Equations</title>
    <p>
      More complicated equations might need a few setup steps before we can do the two important
      steps of isolating the variable term and eliminating the coefficient. Here is a general guide
      for what the full process can be like.
    </p>
    <algorithm xml:id="algorithm-solve-multistep-linear-equation">
      <title>Steps to Solve Linear Equations</title>                                                          <idx><h>Solving</h><h>linear equations</h><h>multistep</h></idx>
      <p>                                                                                                     <idx><h>Linear equations</h><h>solving</h></idx>
        <dl>
          <li>
            <title>Simplify</title>
            <p>
              Simplify the expressions on each side of the equation by distributing and combining
              like terms.
            </p>
          </li>

          <li>
            <title>Separate</title>
            <p>
              Use addition or subtraction to separate the terms so that the variable terms are on
              one side of the equation and the constant terms are on the other side of the equation.
            </p>
          </li>

          <li>
            <title>Clear the Coefficient</title>
            <p>
              Use multiplication or division to eliminate the variable term's coefficient.
            </p>
          </li>

          <li>
            <title>Check</title>
            <p>
              Check the solution in the original equation. Substitute values into the original
              equation and use the order of operations to simplify both sides. It's important to use
              the order of operations alone rather than properties like the distributive law.
              Otherwise you might repeat the same arithmetic errors you (might have) made while
              solving, and fail to catch an incorrect solution.
            </p>
          </li>

          <li>
            <title>Summarize</title>
            <p>
              State the solution set. Or in the case of an application problem, summarize the result
              in a complete sentence using appropriate units.
            </p>
          </li>
        </dl>
      </p>
    </algorithm>

    <example>
      <p>
        Ahmed has <m>\$2500</m> in his savings account and will be saving <m>\$550</m> per month.
        Julia has <m>\$4600</m> in her savings account and will be saving <m>\$250</m> per month. If
        this situation continues, how long will it take for Ahmed to catch up to Julia in savings?
      </p>

      <p>
        Ahmed saves <m>\$550</m> per month, so he can save <m>550t</m> dollars in <m>t</m> months.
        With the <m>\$2500</m> he started with, after <m>t</m> months he has <m>550t + 2500</m>
        dollars. Similarly, after <m>t</m> months, Julia has <m>250t + 4600</m> dollars. To find
        when those two accounts will have the same amount of money, we write the equation
        <md>
          550t + 2500 = 250t + 4600
        </md>
        Each side is simplified, but unlike earlier examples, we have the variable <m>t</m> on
        <em>both</em> side of the equation. We can still use
        <xref ref="fact-properties-of-equivalent-equations" text="custom">properties of equality</xref>
        to end up with only one <m>t</m>-term. We start by subtracting <m>250t</m> from each side.
        <md>
          <mrow>550t+2500\amp=250t+4600</mrow>
          <mrow>550t+2500\subtractright{250t}\amp=250t+4600\subtractright{250t}</mrow>
          <mrow>300t+2500\amp=4600</mrow>
        </md>
        And then subtract a constant term from each side.
        <md>
          <mrow>300t+2500\subtractright{2500}\amp=4600\subtractright{2500}</mrow>
          <mrow>300t\amp=2100</mrow>
        </md>
        Now we can divide by the coefficient.
        <md>
          <mrow>\divideunder{300t}{300}\amp=\divideunder{2100}{300}</mrow>
          <mrow>t\amp=7</mrow>
        </md>
        Checking the solution <m>7</m>:
        <md>
          <mrow>550t+2500\amp=250t+4600</mrow>
          <mrow>550(\substitute{7})+2500\amp\wonder{=}250(\substitute{7})+4600</mrow>
          <mrow>3850+2500\amp\wonder{=}1750+4600</mrow>
          <mrow>6350\amp\confirm{=}6350</mrow>
        </md>
      </p>

      <p>
        Ahmed will catch up to Julia after <m>7</m> months.
      </p>
    </example>

    <exercise xml:id="exercise-two-step-equation-both-sides" label="two-step-equation-both-sides">
      <webwork>
        <pg-code>
          Context("FiniteSolutionSets");
          $solution = Formula("{2}");
        </pg-code>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Solve for <m>x</m> in <m>5-2x=5x-9</m>.
          </p>
         <p>
            <var name="$solution" width="5"/>
          </p>
         </statement>
        <solution>
          <p>
            <md>
              <mrow>5-2x\amp=\nextoperation{5x}-9</mrow>
              <mrow>5-2x\subtractright{5x}\amp=5x-9\subtractright{5x}</mrow>
              <mrow>\nextoperation{5}-7x\amp=-9</mrow>
              <mrow>5-7x\subtractright{5}\amp=-9\subtractright{5}</mrow>
              <mrow>-7x\amp=-14</mrow>
              <mrow>\divideunder{-7x}{-7}\amp=\divideunder{-14}{-7}</mrow>
              <mrow>x\amp=2</mrow>
            </md>
            Checking the solution <m>2</m>:
            <md>
              <mrow>5-2x\amp=5x-9</mrow>
              <mrow>5-2(\substitute{2})\amp\wonder{=}5(\substitute{2})-9</mrow>
              <mrow>5-4\amp\wonder{=}10-9</mrow>
              <mrow>1\amp\confirm{=}1</mrow>
            </md>
            Therefore the solution is <m>2</m> and the solution set is <m>\{2\}</m>.
          </p>
        </solution>
      </webwork>
    </exercise>

    <p>
      In <xref ref="exercise-two-step-equation-both-sides"/>, we could have moved variable terms to
      the <em>right</em> side of the equal sign and number terms to the <em>left</em> side. We chose
      not to, but there's no reason why we couldn't have done that. Let's explore:
      <md>
        <mrow>5-\nextoperation{2x}\amp=5x-9</mrow>
        <mrow>5-2x\addright{2x}\amp=5x-9\addright{2x}</mrow>
        <mrow>5\amp=7x-\nextoperation{9}</mrow>
        <mrow>5\addright{9}\amp=7x-9\addright{9}</mrow>
        <mrow>14\amp=7x</mrow>
        <mrow>\divideunder{14}{7}\amp=\divideunder{7x}{7}</mrow>
        <mrow>2\amp=x</mrow>
      </md>
      The solution is the same either way.
    </p>

    <p>
      Also, we could save a step by moving variable terms and constant terms in one step:
      <md>
        <mrow>5-2x\amp=5x-9</mrow>
        <mrow>5-2x\addright{2x+9}\amp=5x-9\addright{2x+9}</mrow>
        <mrow>14\amp=7x</mrow>
        <mrow>\divideunder{14}{7}\amp=\divideunder{7x}{7}</mrow>
        <mrow>2\amp=x</mrow>
      </md>
      For the sake of a slow and careful explanation, the examples in this chapter will move
      variable terms and number terms in separate steps. You shoudl feel free to add/subtract more
      than one term in one step if you are comfortable with that.
    </p>

    <p>
      The next example requires combining like terms.
    </p>

    <example>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Solve for <m>n</m> in <m>n-9+3n=n-3n</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          We start by combining like terms. After this, we can separate the <m>n</m>-terms and
          constant terms, proceeding as before.
        </p>
        <sidebyside widths="47% 47%" margins="0%">
          <p>
            <md>
              <mrow>n-9+3n\amp=n-3n</mrow>
              <mrow>4n-9\amp=-2n</mrow>
              <mrow>4n-9\subtractright{4n}\amp=-2n\subtractright{4n}</mrow>
              <mrow>-9\amp=-6n</mrow>
              <mrow>\divideunder{-9}{-6}\amp=\divideunder{-6n}{-6}</mrow>
              <mrow>\frac{3}{2}\amp=n</mrow>
            </md>
          </p>

          <p>
            Checking the solution <m>\frac{3}{2}</m>:
            <md>
              <mrow>n-9+3n\amp=n-3n</mrow>
              <mrow>\substitute{\frac{3}{2}}-9+3\left(\substitute{\frac{3}{2}}\right)\amp\wonder{=}\substitute{\frac{3}{2}}-3\left(\substitute{\frac{3}{2}}\right)</mrow>
              <mrow>\frac{3}{2}-9+\frac{9}{2}\amp\wonder{=}\frac{3}{2}-\frac{9}{2}</mrow>
              <mrow>\frac{12}{2}-9\amp\wonder{=}-\frac{6}{2}</mrow>
              <mrow>6-9\amp\confirm{=}-3</mrow>
            </md>
          </p>
        </sidebyside>

        <p>
          The solution to the equation <m>n-9+3n=n-3n</m> is <m>\frac{3}{2}</m> and the solution set
          is <m>\left\{\frac{3}{2}\right\}</m>.
        </p>
      </solution>
    </example>

    <example>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Solve for <m>a</m> in <m>4 - (3 - a)=-2 - 2(2a + 1)</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          This time we start by simplifying each side of the equation, which involves distributing
          as well as combining like terms. Here is a reminder to be careful when distributing a
          negative sign over a group of terms.
        </p>

        <sidebyside widths="47% 47%" margins="0%">
          <p>
            <md>
              <mrow>4-(3-a)\amp=-2-2(2a+1)</mrow>
              <mrow>4-3+a\amp=-2-4a-2</mrow>
              <mrow>1+a\amp=-4-4a</mrow>
              <mrow>1+a\addright{4a}\amp=-4-4a\addright{4a}</mrow>
              <mrow>1+5a\amp=-4</mrow>
              <mrow>1+5a\subtractright{1}\amp=-4\subtractright{1}</mrow>
              <mrow>5a\amp=-5</mrow>
              <mrow>\divideunder{5a}{5}\amp=\divideunder{-5}{5}</mrow>
              <mrow>a\amp=-1</mrow>
            </md>
          </p>

          <p>
            Checking the solution <m>-1</m>:
            <md>
              <mrow>4\nextoperation{{}-(3-a)}\amp=-2\nextoperation{{}-2(2a+1)}</mrow>
              <mrow>4-(3-(\substitute{-1}))\amp\wonder{=}-2-2(2(\substitute{-1})+1)</mrow>
              <mrow>4-(4)\amp\wonder{=}-2-2(-1)</mrow>
              <mrow>0\amp\wonder{=}-2+2</mrow>
              <mrow>0\amp\confirm{=}0</mrow>
            </md>
          </p>
        </sidebyside>

        <p>
          Therefore the solution to the equation is <m>-1</m> and the solution set is <m>\{-1\}</m>.
        </p>
      </solution>
    </example>

    <exercise label="multistep-equation">
      <webwork>
        <pg-code>
          Context("FiniteSolutionSets");
          $solution = Formula("{6}");
        </pg-code>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Solve for <m>x</m> in <m>4 + 3(12 - x) = 12x - 5(2x - 2)</m>.
          </p>
          <p>
            <var name="$solution" width="5"/>
          </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
          <p>
            <md>
              <mrow>4 + \nextoperation{3(12 - x)} \amp= 12x\nextoperation{{}-5(2x - 2)}</mrow>
              <mrow>4 + 36 - 3x \amp= 12x - 10x + 10</mrow>
              <mrow>40 - 3x \amp= 2x + 10</mrow>
              <mrow>40 - 3x\addright{3x} \amp= 2x + 10\addright{3x}</mrow>
              <mrow>40 \amp= 5x + 10</mrow>
              <mrow>40\subtractright{10} \amp= 5x + 10\subtractright{10}</mrow>
              <mrow>30 \amp= 5x</mrow>
              <mrow>\divideunder{30}{5}\amp=\divideunder{5x}{5}</mrow>
              <mrow>6\amp=x</mrow>
            </md>
            Checking the solution <m>6</m>:
            <md>
              <mrow>4 + 3(12 - x) \amp= 12x - 5(2x - 2)</mrow>
              <mrow>4 + 3(12 - \substitute{6}) \amp\wonder{=} 12\substitute{(6)} - 5(2\substitute{(6)} - 2)</mrow>
              <mrow>4 + 3(6) \amp\wonder{=} 72 - 5(12 - 2)</mrow>
              <mrow>4 + 18 \amp\wonder{=} 72 - 5(10)</mrow>
              <mrow>22 \amp\confirm{=} 72 - 50</mrow>
            </md>
            Therefore the solution is <m>6</m> and the solution set is <m>\{6\}</m>.
          </p>
        </solution>
      </webwork>
    </exercise>
  </subsection>

  <subsection>
    <title>Revisiting Applications</title>

    <p>
      In <xref ref="section-modeling-with-equations-and-inequalities"/>, we explored several <q>word
      problem</q> scenarios that led to equations, but we did not try to solve those equations.
      Let's revisit some of those applications and try to solve them.
    </p>

    <p>
      Here we revisit <xref ref="example-bathtub"/>.
    </p>
    <example>
      <statement>
        <p>
          A bathtub contains
          <quantity>
            <mag>2.5</mag><unit base="foot" exp="3"/>
          </quantity>
          of water.
          More water is being poured in at a rate of
          <quantity>
            <mag>1.75</mag><unit base="foot" exp="3"/>
          </quantity>
          per minute. How long will it be until the amount of water in the bathtub reaches
          <quantity>
            <mag>6.25</mag><unit base="foot" exp="3"/>
          </quantity>?
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          We have an initial amount of water
          (<quantity>
            <mag>2.5</mag><unit base="foot" exp="3"/>
          </quantity>),
          a rate at which the amount of water is changing
          (<quantity>
            <mag>1.75</mag><unit base="foot" exp="3"/><per base="minute"/>
          </quantity>),
          and a final amount of water we are going to reach
          (<quantity>
            <mag>6.25</mag><unit base="foot" exp="3"/>
          </quantity>).
          So we can use the pattern for rate modeling from <xref ref="men-rate-model"/>.
        </p>
        <p>
          We should clearly identify the variable first though. The solution is supposed to
          represent an amount of time. So a reasonable variable to use is <m>t</m>. Let <m>t</m>
          be the amount of time, in minutes, that it takes for the tub to reach
          <quantity>
            <mag>6.25</mag><unit base="foot" exp="3"/>
          </quantity>.
          And we have the equation:
          <md>
            2.5 + 1.75t = 6.25
          </md>
          Now we have the skills to solve this equation.
          <md>
            <mrow>2.5 + 1.75t \amp= 6.25</mrow>
            <mrow>2.5 + 1.75t\subtractright{2.5} \amp= 6.25\subtractright{2.5}</mrow>
            <mrow>1.75t\amp= 3.75</mrow>
            <mrow>\divideunder{1.75t}{1.75}\amp=\divideunder{3.75}{1.75}</mrow>
            <mrow>t\amp\approx2.14</mrow>
          </md>
          So it will take about <m>2.14</m> minutes for the tub to have
          <quantity>
            <mag>6.25</mag><unit base="foot" exp="3"/>
          </quantity>
          of water.
        </p>
      </solution>
    </example>

    <p>
      Here we revisit <xref ref="example-salary-increase"/>.
    </p>
    <example>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Jakobi's annual salary as a nurse this year is <m>\$73{,}290</m>. That's following a
          <m>4\%</m> raise over last year's salary. What was his salary the previous year?
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          As soon as you understand that the solution will be Jakobi's salary from last year, that
          is when you should clearly define a variable. Since it will represent a salary, we choose
          to use <m>S</m> as the variable. Let <m>S</m> represent Jakobi's salary from last year.
        </p>
        <p>
          To set up the equation, we need to think about how he arrived at this year's salary. His
          employer took last year's salary and added <m>4\%</m> to that. In words, we have:
          <md>
            \text{lastYear'sSalary}+(4\%\text{ of lastYear'sSalary} = \text{thisYear'sSalary}
          </md>
          We represent <q><m>4\%</m> of lastYear'sSalary</q> with <m>0.04S</m> since <m>0.04</m>
          is the decimal equivalent to <m>4\%</m>. So out equation is:
          <md>
            S + 0.04S = 73290
          </md>
          Now we have the skills to solve this equation.
          <md>
            <mrow>S + 0.04S \amp= 73290</mrow>
            <mrow>1.04S \amp= 73290</mrow>
            <mrow>\divideunder{1.04S}{1.04}\amp=\divideunder{73290}{1.04}</mrow>
            <mrow>S\amp\approx70471</mrow>
          </md>
          So last year, Jakobi's salary was about <m>\$70{,}471</m>.
        </p>
      </solution>
    </example>


    <p>
      Here we revisit <xref ref="exercise-shirt"/>.
    </p>
    <exercise label="shirt-part-two">
      <webwork>
        <pg-code>
          Context("Currency")->currency->addSymbol("dollars","dollar");
          Context()->flags->set(trimTrailingZeros=>1);
          $cost = Currency(63.75);
        </pg-code>
        <statement>
          <p>
            A shirt is on sale for <m>20\%</m> off. The sale price is <m>\$51.00</m>. What was the
            shirt's original price?
          </p>
          <p>
            <var name="$cost" width="16" />
          </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
          <p>
            Let <m>x</m> represent the original price of the shirt. Since <m>20\%</m> is removed to
            bring the cost down to <m>\$51</m>, we can set up the equation:
            <md>
              <mrow>\pinover{x}{original}\pinover{-}{minus}\pinover{0.20}{20\%}\pinover{\cdot}{of}\pinover{x}{original}\amp\pinover{=}{is}\pinover{51}{\$51}</mrow>
            </md>
            Now we have the skills to solve this equation.
            <md>
              <mrow>x - 0.20x \amp= 51</mrow>
              <mrow>0.80x \amp= 51</mrow>
              <mrow>\divideunder{0.80x}{0.80}\amp=\divideunder{51}{0.80}</mrow>
              <mrow>x\amp=63.75</mrow>
            </md>
            The shirt's original price was <m>\$63.75</m>.
          </p>
        </solution>
      </webwork>
    </exercise>
  </subsection>

  <!-- <subsection>
    <title>Differentiating between Simplifying Expressions, Evaluating Expressions and Solving Equations</title>
    <p>
      Consider the following three examples, which have similarities on the surface, but are
      fundamentally different from each other.
    </p>

    <example xml:id="example-differentiate-simplify-expressions">
      <statement>
        <p>
          Simplify the expression <m>10-3(x+2)</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          Distribute the <m>-3</m> and then combine like terms.
          <md>
            <mrow>10-3(x+2)\amp=10-3x-6</mrow>
            <mrow>\amp=-3x+4</mrow>
          </md>
          Note that our final result is an <em>expression</em>.
        </p>
      </solution>
    </example>

    <example xml:id="example-differentiate-evaluate-expressions">
      <statement>
        <p>
          Evaluate the expression <m>10-3(x+2)</m> when <m>x=2</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          Substitute <m>2</m> in for <m>x</m> in the expression:
          <md>
            <mrow>10-3(x+2)\amp=10-3(\substitute{2}+2)</mrow>
            <mrow>\amp=10-3(4)</mrow>
            <mrow>\amp=10-12</mrow>
            <mrow>\amp=-2</mrow>
          </md>
          Note that our final result here is a <em>number</em>.
        </p>
      </solution>
    </example>

    <example xml:id="example-differentiate-solve-equations">
      <statement>
        <p>
          Solve the equation <m>10-3(x+2)=x-16</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          Follow the process we have been using in this section to solve a linear equation.
          <md>
            <mrow>10-3(x+2)\amp=x-16</mrow>
            <mrow>10-3x-6\amp=x-16</mrow>
            <mrow>-3x+4\amp=x-16</mrow>
            <mrow>-3x+4\subtractright{x}\amp=x-16\subtractright{x}</mrow>
            <mrow>-4x+4\amp=-16</mrow>
            <mrow>-4x+4\subtractright{4}\amp=-16\subtractright{4}</mrow>
            <mrow>-4x\amp=-20</mrow>
            <mrow>\divideunder{-4x}{-4}\amp=\divideunder{-20}{-4}</mrow>
            <mrow>x\amp=5</mrow>
          </md>
          So the solution set is <m>\{5\}</m>.
        </p>
        <p>
          Note that our final result here is a <em>solution set</em>.
        </p>
      </solution>
    </example>

    <p>
      <term>Simplifying</term>, <term>evaluating</term>, and <term>solving</term> are three
      different algebra tasks. Students often use these vocabulary terms incorrectly, using one when
      they meant another. Here is a summary collection of the differences that you should understand
      between these algebra tasks.
    </p>

    <list xml:id="list-differences-expressions-equations">
      <title>A summary the differences between simplifying expressions, evaluating expressions, and solving equations.</title>
      <ul>
        <li>
          <p>
            An expression like <m>10-3(x+2)</m> can be <term>simplified</term> to <m>-3x+4</m> (as
            in <xref ref="example-differentiate-simplify-expressions"/>). However we cannot
            <q>solve</q> an expression like this. It is incorrect to say you will <q>solve
            <m>10-3(x+2)</m></q>.
          </p>
        </li>

        <li>
          <p>
            An expression like <m>10-3(x+2)</m> can be <term>evaluated</term>, but only once you
            have a number to use in place of the variable. This is what happens in
            <xref ref="example-differentiate-evaluate-expressions"/>, where <m>x=2</m>, and the
            expression evaluates to <m>-2</m>.
          </p>
        </li>

        <li>
          <p>
            An equation connects two expressions with an equal sign. In
            <xref ref="example-differentiate-solve-equations"/>, <m>10-3(x+2)=x-16</m> has one
            expression on either side of equal sign. You can <term>solve</term> this equation,
            because it is an equation. You can also solve inequalities. You just cannot solve an
            expression like <m>10-3(x+2)</m>.
          </p>
        </li>

        <li>
          <p>
            When we solve the equation <m>10-3(x+2)=x-16</m>, we are looking for a number which
            makes those two expressions evaluate to the same value. In
            <xref ref="example-differentiate-solve-equations"/>, we found the solution was <m>5</m>.
            That number <m>5</m> makes both <m>10-3(x+2)</m> and <m>x-16</m> evaluate to the same
            number (and that number is <m>-11</m> if you were curious.)
          </p>
        </li>
      </ul>
    </list>

    <exercise label="matching-simplify-evaluate-solvee">
      <title>Matching Vocabulary</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Match each piece of mathematics with the task that is most likely to be something you
          would do with it.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <cardsort>
        <match>
            <premise order="3"><m>7x+4+x</m></premise>
            <response>Simplify</response>
        </match>
        <match>
            <premise order="1"><m>7x+4+x, x=0</m></premise>
            <response>Evaluate</response>
        </match>
        <match>
            <premise order="2"><m>7x+4=x</m></premise>
            <response>Solve</response>
        </match>
      </cardsort>
    </exercise>
  </subsection> -->

  <subsection>
    <title>Solving Multistep Inequalities</title>
    <p>
      When solving a linear inequality, we almost follow the exact same steps as we do in
      <xref ref="algorithm-solve-multistep-linear-equation"/>. One difference is that when we
      multiply or divide by a negative number on both sides of an inequality, the direction of the
      inequality symbol must switch. The other difference is that checking a solution set takes more
      effort.
    </p>

    <algorithm xml:id="algorithm-solve-linear-inequality">
      <title>Steps to Solve Linear Inequalities</title>                                                       <idx><h>Solving</h><h>linear inequalities</h><h>multistep</h></idx>
                                                                                                              <idx><h>Linear inequalities</h><h>solving</h></idx>
                                                                                                              <idx><h>Equation(s)</h><h>using both addition and multiplication properties</h></idx>
      <p>
        <dl>
          <li>
            <title>Simplify</title>
            <p>
              Simplify the expressions on each side of the inequality by distributing and combining
              like terms.
            </p>
          </li>

          <li>
            <title>Separate</title>
            <p>
              Use addition or subtraction to separate the terms so that the variable terms are on
              one side of the inequality and the constant terms are on the other side of the
              inequality.
            </p>
          </li>

          <li>
            <title>Clear the Coefficient</title>
            <p>
              Use multiplication or division to eliminate the variable term's coefficient. <alert>If
              you multiply or divide each side by a negative number, switch the direction of the
              inequality symbol.</alert>
            </p>
          </li>

          <li>
            <title>Check</title>
            <p>
              A solution to a linear inequality has a <q>boundary number</q>. Using the original
              inequality, check (1) a number less than the boundary number, (2) the boundary number
              itself, and (3) a number greater than the boundary number to confirm what should and
              shouldn't be solutions are all working as expected. (This can take time, so use your
              judgment about when you might get away with skipping this checking.)
            </p>
          </li>

          <li>
            <title>Summarize</title>
            <p>
              State the solution set. Or in the case of an application problem, summarize the result
              in a complete sentence using appropriate units.
            </p>
          </li>
        </dl>
      </p>
    </algorithm>

    <example xml:id="example-inequality-simple">
      <statement>
        <p>
          Solve for <m>t</m> in the inequality <m>-3t+5\geq11</m>.
          Write the solution set in both set-builder notation and interval notation.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          We'll handle this much like we would handle an equation, at least for the first step.
          <md>
            <mrow>-3t+5\amp\geq11</mrow>
            <mrow>-3t+5\subtractright{5}\amp\geq11\subtractright{5}</mrow>
            <mrow>-3t\amp\geq6</mrow>
            <mrow>\divideunder{-3t}{-3}\amp\mathbin{\secondhighlight{\le}}\divideunder{6}{-3}</mrow>
            <mrow>t\amp\leq-2</mrow>
          </md>
        </p>

        <p>
          Note that when we divided both sides of the inequality by <m>-3</m>, we had to switch the
          direction of the inequality symbol. At this point we think that the solution set in
          set-builder notation is <m>\{t\mid t\leq-2\}</m>, and the solution set in interval
          notation is <m>(-\infty,-2]</m>.
        </p>

        <p>
          Since there are infinitely many solutions, it's impossible to literally check them all. We
          believe that all values of <m>t</m> for which <m>t\leq-2</m> are solutions. We check that
          one number less than <m>-2</m> (any number, your choice) satisfies the inequality.
          <em>And</em> that <m>-2</m> satisfies the inequality. <em>And</em> that one number greater
          than <m>-2</m> (any number, your choice) does <em>not</em> satisfy the inequality. We
          choose to check the values <m>-10</m>, <m>-2</m>, and <m>0</m>.
        </p>

        <image>
          <shortdescription>
            a number line with a mark at -2; a thick line overlays the number line to the left of -2
            with an arrow pointing left; there is a right bracket at -2; three arrows point to -10,
            -2, and 0 on the number line, suggesting that these values will be checked as possible
            solutions
          </shortdescription>
          <latex-image>
            \begin{tikzpicture}
              \begin{axis}[
                  numberline,
                  xmin=-10,
                  xmax=10,
                  xtick={-10,-8,...,10},
                  minor xtick={-9,-7,...,9},
                ]
                \addplot[infiniteclosedinterval] coordinates {(-10,0) (-2,0)};
                \node (A) at (axis cs:-10,1) {$-10\text{?}$};
                \draw[->] (A) -- (axis cs:-10,0);
                \node (B) at (axis cs:-2,2) {$-2\text{?}$};
                \draw[->] (B) -- (axis cs:-2,0);
                \node (C) at (axis cs:2,1) {$0\text{?}$};
                \draw[->] (C) -- (axis cs:0,0);
              \end{axis}
            \end{tikzpicture}
          </latex-image>
        </image>

        <p>
          <md>
            <mrow>\amp\amp -3t+5\amp\ge11\amp \amp</mrow>
            <mrow>-3(\substitute{-10})+5\amp\wonder{\geq}11\amp -3(\substitute{-2})+5\amp\wonder{\geq}11\amp -3(\substitute{0})+5\amp\wonder{\geq}11</mrow>
            <mrow>30+5\amp\wonder{\geq}11\amp 6+5\amp\wonder{\geq}11\amp 0+5\amp\wonder{\geq}11</mrow>
            <mrow>35\amp\confirm{\geq}11\amp 11\amp\confirm{\geq}11\amp 5\amp\reject{\geq}11</mrow>
          </md>
          So both <m>-10</m> and <m>-2</m> are solutions as expected, while <m>0</m> is not. This is
          evidence that our solution set is correct. Making these checks would help us catch an
          error if we had made one. While it certainly does take time and space to make three checks
          like this, it has its value.
        </p>
      </solution>
    </example>

    <example>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Solve for <m>z</m> in the inequality <m>(6z+5)-(2z-3)\gt-12</m>.
          Write the solution set in both set-builder notation and interval notation.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          Here, our first step will be simplifying the left side.
          <md>
            <mrow>(6z+5)-(2z-3)\amp\gt-12</mrow>
            <mrow>6z+5-2z+3\amp\gt-12</mrow>
            <mrow>4z+8\amp\gt-12</mrow>
            <mrow>4z+8\subtractright{8}\amp\gt-12\subtractright{8}</mrow>
            <mrow>4z\amp\gt-20</mrow>
            <mrow>\divideunder{4z}{4}\amp\gt\divideunder{-20}{4}</mrow>
            <mrow>z\amp\gt -5</mrow>
          </md>
        </p>

        <p>
          Note that we divided both sides of the inequality by <m>4</m> and since this is a positive
          number we did <em>not</em> need to switch the direction of the inequality symbol. At this
          point we think that the solution set in set-builder notation is <m>\{z\mid z\gt-5\}</m>,
          and the solution set in interval notation is <m>(-5,\infty)</m>.
        </p>

        <p>
          Since there are infinitely many solutions, it's impossible to literally check them all. We
          believe that all values of <m>z</m> for which <m>z\gt-5</m> are solutions. We check that
          one number less than <m>-5</m> (any number, your choice) does <em>not</em> satisfy the
          inequality. <em>And</em> that <m>-5</m> does <em>not</em> satisfy the inequality.
          <em>And</em> that one number greater than <m>-5</m> (any number, your choice)
          <em>does</em> satisfy the inequality. We choose to check the values <m>-10</m>, <m>-5</m>,
          and <m>0</m>.
        </p>

        <image>
          <shortdescription>
            a number line with a mark at -5; a thick line overlays the number line to the right of
            -5 with an arrow pointing right; there is a left parenthesis at -5; three arrows point
            to -10, -5, and 0 on the number line, suggesting that these values will be checked as
            possible solutions
          </shortdescription>
          <latex-image>
            \begin{tikzpicture}
              \begin{axis}[
                  numberline,
                  xmin=-10,
                  xmax=10,
                  xtick={-10,-8,...,10},
                  minor xtick={-9,-7,...,9},
                ]
                  \addplot[openinfiniteinterval] coordinates {(-5,0) (10,0)};
                  \node (A) at (axis cs:-10,1) {$-10\text{?}$};
                  \draw[->] (A) -- (axis cs:-10,0);
                  \node (B) at (axis cs:-5,2) {$-5\text{?}$};
                  \draw[->] (B) -- (axis cs:-5,0);
                  \node (C) at (axis cs:0,1) {$0\text{?}$};
                  \draw[->] (C) -- (axis cs:0,0);
              \end{axis}
            \end{tikzpicture}
          </latex-image>
        </image>

        <p>
          <md>
            <mrow>(6(\substitute{-10})+5)-(2(\substitute{-10})-3)\amp\wonder{\gt}-12</mrow>
            <mrow>(-60+5)-(-20-3)\amp\wonder{\gt}-12</mrow>
            <mrow>-55-(-23)\amp\wonder{\gt}-12</mrow>
            <mrow>-32\amp\reject{\gt}-12</mrow>
          </md>
          <md>
            <mrow>(6(\substitute{-5})+5)-(2(\substitute{-5})-3)\amp\wonder{\gt}-12</mrow>
            <mrow>(-30+5)-(-10-3)\amp\wonder{\gt}-12</mrow>
            <mrow>-25-(-13)\amp\wonder{\gt}-12</mrow>
            <mrow>-12\amp\reject{\gt}-12</mrow>
          </md>
          <md>
            <mrow>(6(\substitute{0})+5)-(2(\substitute{0})-3)\amp\wonder{\gt}-12</mrow>
            <mrow>(0+5)-(0-3)\amp\wonder{\gt}-12</mrow>
            <mrow>5-(-3)\amp\wonder{\gt}-12</mrow>
            <mrow>8\amp\confirm{\gt}-12</mrow>
          </md>
          So both <m>-10</m> and <m>-5</m> are not solutions as expected, while <m>0</m> is a
          solution. This is evidence that our solution set is correct. The solution set in
          set-builder notation is <m>\{z\mid z\gt-5\}</m>. The solution set in interval notation is
          <m>(-5,\infty)</m>.
        </p>
      </solution>
    </example>

    <exercise label="solve-inequality">
      <webwork>
        <pg-macros>
          <macro-file>parserGraphTool.pl</macro-file>
        </pg-macros>
        <pg-code>
          Context("Interval");
          $interval = Interval("(-inf,-1)");
          InequalitySetBuilder::UseVerticalSuchThat();
          Context("InequalitySetBuilder-Only");
          $setbuilder = Compute("{ x | x&lt;-1}");
          $gt = GraphTool("{interval, $interval}")->with(
            availableTools => ['IntervalTool', 'IncludeExcludePointTool'],
            numberLine => 1,
            xAxisLabel => 'x',
            bBox => [ -8, 8 ],
            ticksDistanceX => 1,
            minorTicksX => 0,
            useBracketEnds => 1,
            showInStatic => 0,
            showCoordinateHints => 0,
          );
        </pg-code>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Solve the inequality <m>-2-2(2x+1)\gt4-(3-x)</m>. Graph the solution set on a number
            line. State the solution set using both interval notation and set-builder notation.
          </p>
          <p>
            <var name="$gt" width="1"/>
          </p>
          <instruction>
            In interval notation.
          </instruction>
          <p>
            <var name="$interval" width="12"/>
          </p>
          <instruction>
            In set-builder notation. (If needed, type <c>inf</c> or <c>infinity</c>
            for <m>\infty</m>, <c>&gt;=</c> for <m>\geq</m>, and <c>&lt;=</c> for <m>\leq</m>.)
          </instruction>
          <p>
            <var name="$setbuilder" width="12"/>
          </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
          <p>
            We start by simplifying the two sides.
            <md>
              <mrow>-2-2(2x+1)\amp\gt4-(3-x)</mrow>
              <mrow>-2-4x-2\amp\gt4-3+x</mrow>
              <mrow>-4x-4\amp\gt1+x</mrow>
            </md>
            And now add/subtract terms to separate the variable terms and the constant terms.
            <md>
              <mrow>-4x-4\addright{4}\subtractright{x}\amp\gt1+x\addright{4}\subtractright{x}</mrow>
              <mrow>-5x\amp\gt5</mrow>
            </md>
            And now divide each side by <m>-5</m>. Since we are dividing by a negative number, the
            inequality sign will change direction.
            <md>x\lt-1</md>
          </p>

          <p>
            Graphically, we represent this solution set as:
          </p>

          <image>
            <latex-image>
              \begin{tikzpicture}
                \begin{axis}[numberline]
                  \addplot[infiniteopeninterval] coordinates {(-10,0) (-1,0)};
                \end{axis}
              \end{tikzpicture}
            </latex-image>
          </image>

          <p>
            Using interval notation, we write the solution set as <m>(-\infty,-1)</m>. Using
            set-builder notation, we write it as <m>\{x \mid x \lt -1\}</m>.
          </p>

          <p>
            We should check that some number less than <m>-11</m> <em>is</em> a solution, that
            <m>-1</m> itself is <em>not</em> a solution, and that some number greater than <m>-1</m>
            is <em>not</em> a solution.
            <md>
              <mrow>-2-2(2(\substitute{-2})+1)\amp\wonder{\gt}4-(3-(\substitute{-2}))</mrow>
              <mrow>-2-2(-4+1)\amp\wonder{\gt}4-5</mrow>
              <mrow>-2-2(-3)\amp\wonder{\gt}-1</mrow>
              <mrow>-2+6\amp\wonder{\gt}-1</mrow>
              <mrow>4\amp\confirm{\gt}-1</mrow>
            </md>
            <md>
              <mrow>-2-2(2(\substitute{-1})+1)\amp\wonder{\gt}4-(3-(\substitute{-1})) \amp -2-2(2(\substitute{0})+1)\amp\wonder{\gt}4-(3-(\substitute{0}))</mrow>
              <mrow>-2-2(-2+1)\amp\wonder{\gt}4-4 \amp -2-2(0+1)\amp\wonder{\gt}4-3</mrow>
              <mrow>-2-2(-1)\amp\wonder{\gt}0 \amp -2-2(1)\amp\wonder{\gt}1</mrow>
              <mrow>-2+2\amp\wonder{\gt}0 \amp -2-2\amp\wonder{\gt}1</mrow>
              <mrow>0\amp\reject{\gt}0 \amp -4\amp\reject{\gt}1</mrow>
            </md>
            Everything worked out as expected, so our solution is reasonably checked.
          </p>
        </solution>
      </webwork>
    </exercise>

    <example>
      <title>Rate Problem</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          When an experiment started, the pressure inside a gas container was <m>4.2</m> atm (one
          atm is the standard pressure air at sea level). As the container was heated, the pressure
          increased by <m>0.7</m> atm per minute. The maximum pressure the container is rated to
          handle is <m>21.7</m> atm. Heating must be stopped once the pressure reaches <m>21.7</m>
          atm. Over what time interval was the container in a safe state (meaning the pressure was
          less than or equal to <m>21.7</m> atm)?
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          This is a situation where something had an initial value (the pressure starts at
          <m>4.2</m> atm) and then changed at a constant rate (it increased by <m>0.7</m> atm per
          minute). So we can use
          <xref ref="men-rate-model" text="custom">the rate model formula</xref>. Except we are not
          exactly interested in the pressure <em>equaling</em> the final value of <m>21.7</m> atm.
          Instead, we are asked about when the pressure was <em>less than or equal to</em>
          <m>21.7</m> atm. So we have the inequality:
          <md>
            <mrow>0.7t+4.2\amp\leq21.7</mrow>
            <mrow>0.7t+4.2\subtractright{4.2}\amp\leq21.7\subtractright{4.2}</mrow>
            <mrow>0.7t\amp\leq17.5</mrow>
            <mrow>\divideunder{0.7t}{0.7}\amp\leq\divideunder{17.5}{0.7}</mrow>
            <mrow>t\amp\leq25</mrow>
          </md>
        </p>
        <p>
          In summary, the container was safe as long as <m>t\leq25</m>. Assuming that the time
          <m>t</m> also must be greater than or equal to zero, this means <m>0\leq t\leq 25</m>. We
          can write this as the time interval as <m>[0,25]</m>. Thus the container was safe between
          <m>0</m> minutes and <m>25</m> minutes.
        </p>
      </solution>
    </example>

    <example>
      <title>Percent Problem</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          The population of a certain country grew by <m>7\%</m> over the course of the past decade.
          One town in this country grew in population too, but not as fast as the country did
          overall. Its current population is <m>22{,}341</m>. What might its population have been
          ten years ago?
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          Let <m>x</m> be the town's population from ten years ago. If the town had grown by
          <m>7\%</m>, then it's population would be <m>x + 0.07x</m>. But since it actually grew
          less quickly than <m>7\%</m> per decade, <m>x + 0.07x</m> would work out to more than the
          town's current population of <m>22{,}341</m>. So we have the inequality:
          <md>
            <mrow>x + 0.07x\amp\gt22341</mrow>
            <mrow>1.07x\amp\gt22341</mrow>
            <mrow>\divideunder{1.07x}{1.07}\amp\gt\divideunder{22341}{1.07}</mrow>
            <mrow>x\amp\gt20879.4\ldots</mrow>
          </md>
        </p>
        <p>
          So the town's population from ten years ago was at least <m>20880</m>.
        </p>
      </solution>
    </example>
  </subsection>

  <subsection>
    <title>Special Solution Sets</title>
    <p>
      Recall that for the equation <m>x+2=5</m>, there is only one number which will make the
      equation true: <m>3</m>. This means that the solution is <m>3</m>, and we write the
      <term>solution set</term> as <m>\{3\}</m>. We say the equation's solution set has one
      <term>element</term>, <m>3</m>.
    </p>

    <p>
      We'll now explore equations where <em>all real numbers</em> are solutions, and other equations
      where <em>no real number</em> is a solution.
    </p>

    <example>                                                                                                 <idx><h>Linear equations</h><h>with no solution</h></idx>
      <p>
        Solve for <m>x</m> in <m>3x=3x+4</m>.
      </p>
      <p>
        To solve this equation, we need to move all terms containing <m>x</m> to one side of the
        equal sign. We set out to remove the <m>3x</m> from the right side of the equation, by
        subtracting <m>3x</m> from each side:
        <md>
          <mrow>3x\amp=3x+4</mrow>
          <mrow>3x\subtractright{3x}\amp=3x+4\subtractright{3x}</mrow>
          <mrow>0\amp=4</mrow>
        </md>
      </p>
      <p>
        But now <m>x</m> is no longer present in the equation. Our effort to remove <m>3x</m> from            <idx><h>Empty set</h></idx>
        the <em>right</em> side coincidentally removed it from the <em>left</em> side too. What
        value can we substitute in for <m>x</m> to make <m>0=4</m> become true? That's a trick
        question; you could never make <m>0=4</m> become true. We say this equation has <q>no
        solution</q>. Or we say that the equation has an <q>empty solution set</q>. We can write an
        empty solution set as <m>\emptyset</m>, or <m>\{\text{ }\}</m>. (Be careful not to confuse
        the empty set symbol <m>\emptyset</m> with the number zero, <m>0</m>.)
      </p>
      <p>
        The equation <m>0=4</m> is unambiguously false no matter what <m>x</m> might be. This shows
        us there is no solution to the original equation.
      </p>
    </example>

    <example xml:id="example-solving-linear-equation-identity-intro">                                         <idx><h>Linear equations</h><h>with infinitely many solutions</h></idx>
      <p>
        Solve for <m>x</m> in <m>2x+1=2x+1</m>.
      </p>
      <p>
        We will move all terms containing <m>x</m> to one side of the equal sign:
        <md>
          <mrow>2x+1\amp=2x+1</mrow>
          <mrow>2x+1\subtractright{2x}\amp=2x+1\subtractright{2x}</mrow>
          <mrow>1\amp=1</mrow>
        </md>
      </p>
      <p>
        Once again, <m>x</m> is no longer present in the equation. What value can we substitute in
        for <m>x</m> to make <m>1=1</m> be true? This is another trick question; <em>any</em> value
        for <m>x</m> would work. This means that all real numbers are solutions to the equation
        <m>2x+1=2x+1</m>. We say this equation's solution set contains <em>all real numbers</em>.
        We can write this set using interval notation as <m>(-\infty,\infty)</m>, or use
        <m>\mathbb{R}</m> as an abbreviation for the set of all real numbers.
      </p>

      <p>
        The equation <m>1=1</m> is unambiguously true no matter what <m>x</m> might be. This shows
        us that all real numbers are solutions to the original linear equation.
      </p>
    </example>

    <remark>
      <p>
        What would have happened if we had continued the solving process after we obtained
        <m>1=1</m> in <xref ref="example-solving-linear-equation-identity-intro"/>?
        <md>
          <mrow>1\amp=1</mrow>
          <mrow>1\subtractright{1}\amp=1\subtractright{1}</mrow>
          <mrow>0\amp=0</mrow>
        </md>
        All we found was another unambiguously true equation, and we still conclude that all real
        numbers are solutions.
      </p>
    </remark>

    <warning>
      <p>
        Note that there is a very important difference when our process ends with <m>0=0</m>,
        compared to when it ends with <m>x=0</m>. The first equation is true no matter what the
        value of <m>x</m> is, and the solution set is <m>(-\infty,\infty)</m>. The second situation
        only has one solution, <m>0</m>, and the solution set is <m>\{0\}</m>.
      </p>
    </warning>

    <example>                                                                                                 <idx><h>Inequalities</h><h>with infinitely many solutions</h></idx>
      <p>
        Solve for <m>t</m> in the inequality <m>4t+5\gt 4t+2</m>.
      </p>
      <p>
        To solve for <m>t</m>, we aim to eliminate that <m>4t</m> on the right side by subtracting
        <m>4t</m> from each side:
        <md>
          <mrow>4t+5\amp\gt 4t+2</mrow>
          <mrow>4t+5\subtractright{4t}\amp\gt 4t+2\subtractright{4t}</mrow>
          <mrow>5\amp\gt 2</mrow>
        </md>
        We again find ourselves with the variable completely eliminated from <em>both</em> sides.
        What values of <m>t</m> would make the inequality <m>5\gt 2</m> true? The answer is that
        <em>all values</em> of <m>t</m> make <m>5\gt 2</m>, which we know is a strange sounding
        sentence. So our solution set is all real numbers, which we can write as
        <m>(-\infty,\infty)</m> or <m>\mathbb{R}</m>.
      </p>
    </example>

    <example xml:id="example-solving-linear-inequality-false-statement-intro">                                <idx><h>Inequalities</h><h>with no solutions</h></idx>
      <p>
        Solve for <m>x</m> in the inequality <m>-5x+1\le -5x</m>.
      </p>

      <p>
        To solve for <m>x</m>, we aim to eliminate the <m>5x</m> from the right side by adding
        <m>5x</m> to each side:
        <md>
          <mrow>-5x+1\amp\le -5x</mrow>
          <mrow>-5x+1\addright{5x}\amp\le -5x\addright{5x}</mrow>
          <mrow>1\amp\le 0</mrow>
        </md>
        And yet again, the variable has gone missing. We can ask ourselves, <q>For which values of
        <m>x</m> is <m>1\le 0</m> true?</q> The answer is that this is impossible. There is no
        solution to this inequality. We can write the solution set using <m>\emptyset</m> or just
        say that there are <q>no solutions</q>.
      </p>
    </example>

    <p>
      Let's summarize these two special cases that sometimes arise when solving linear equations and
      inequalities.
    </p>

    <list xml:id="list-special-solution-sets">
      <title>Special Solution Sets for Equations and Inequalities</title>
      <dl>
        <li>
          <title>All Real Numbers</title>
          <p>
            When solving an equation or inequality boils down to an unambiguously true equation or
            inequality such as <m>2=2</m> or <m>0\lt2</m>, then all real numbers are solutions.
            We write this solution set as <m>(-\infty,\infty)</m> or <m>\mathbb{R}</m>.
          </p>
        </li>

        <li>
          <title>No Solution</title>
          <p>
            When solving an equation or inequality boils down to an outright false statement such as
            <m>0=2</m> or <m>0\gt2</m>, then no real number is a solution. We write this solution
            set as either <m>\{\ \}</m> or <m>\emptyset</m> or write in words something like
            <q>there are no solutions</q>.
          </p>
        </li>
      </dl>
    </list>
  </subsection>

  <subsection>
    <title>Solving for a Variable</title>
    <sidebyside widths="50% 40%" margins="0%">
      <p>
        The formula of calculating a rectangle's area is <m>A=\ell w</m>, where <m>\ell</m> stands
        for the rectangle's length and <m>w</m> stands for its width. When a rectangle's length and
        width are given, this formula lets us calculate the rectangle's area.
      </p>

      <image width="40%">
        <latex-image label="rectangle-with-known-dimensions">
          \begin{tikzpicture}
            \draw[fill=wood] (0,0) --++  (4,0) node[below, pos=0.5]{\(w\checkmark\)} --++ (0,2.5) node[right, pos=0.5]{\(\ell\checkmark\)} -| cycle;
            \node at (2,1.25) {\(A?\)};
          \end{tikzpicture}
        </latex-image>
      </image>
    </sidebyside>
    <sidebyside widths="50% 40%" margins="0%">
      <p>
        What if we know a rectangle's <em>area</em> and <em>length</em>, but we need to calculate
        its width?
      </p>
      <image width="40%">
        <latex-image label="rectangle-with-known-area-and-length">
          \begin{tikzpicture}
            \draw[fill=wood] (0,0) --++  (4,0) node[below, pos=0.5]{\(w?\)} --++ (0,2.5) node[right, pos=0.5]{\(\ell\checkmark\)} -| cycle;
            \node at (2,1.25) {\(A\checkmark\)};
          \end{tikzpicture}
        </latex-image>
      </image>
    </sidebyside>

    <p>
      Well, if a rectangle's area is
      <quantity>
        <mag>12</mag><unit base="meter" exp="2"/>
      </quantity>, and its length is
      <quantity>
        <mag>4</mag><unit base="meter"/>
      </quantity>, we <em>could</em> substitute these values into the area formula and then we have
      only one variable left, <m>w</m>, and we can solve for it:
      <md>
        <mrow>\substitute{12}\amp=\substitute{4}w</mrow>
        <mrow>\divideunder{12}{4}\amp=\divideunder{4w}{4}</mrow>
        <mrow>3\amp=w\implies w=3</mrow>
      </md>
    </p>

    <p>
      However we can go through the same steps <em>without</em> using specific numbers for <m>A</m>
      and
      <m>\ell</m>:
      <md>
        <mrow>\substitute{A}\amp=\substitute{\ell}w</mrow>
        <mrow>\divideunder{A}{\ell}\amp=\divideunder{\ell w}{\ell}</mrow>
        <mrow>\frac{A}{\ell}\amp=w\implies w =\frac{A}{\ell}</mrow>
      </md>
    </p>

    <p>
      Now we have an equation where <m>w</m> is isolated. For example if we want to find the width
      when <m>A=12</m> and <m>\ell=4</m>, we have a formula: <m>w=\frac{A}{\ell}=\frac{12}{4}=3</m>.
      This formula can be used again: what if <m>A=100</m> and <m>\ell=20</m>?  Or if <m>A=23.47</m>
      and <m>\ell=2.71</m>?  This formula, <m>w=\frac{A}{\ell}</m>, is a handy alternative to the
      original formula <m>A=\ell w</m> for situations where <m>w</m> is the unknown value.
    </p>

    <p>
      Note that when solving for <m>A</m>, we <em>divided</em> each side of the equation by
      <m>\ell</m>. Why exactly? We were trying to isolate <m>w</m>, and <m>w</m> was being
      <em>multiplied</em> by <m>\ell</m>. It's key to understand that we applied the opposite action
      (dividing by <m>\ell</m>) to what was happening to our target variable. We will think in terms
      of <q>un-doing</q> actions as we continue.
    </p>

    <example xml:id="example-solve-for-variable-profit-revenue-cost">
      <p>
        Solve for <m>R</m> in <m>P=R-C</m>. (This is the relationship in economics between profit,
        revenue, and cost.)
      </p>
      <p>
        To solve for <m>R</m>, we notice what is happening to <m>R</m> in this equation: <m>C</m>
        is <em>subtracted</em> from <m>R</m>. To undo this, we <em>add</em> <m>C</m> to each side.
        As we track our steps below, we'll emphasize which variable it is that we are trying to
        isolate. With more than one variable here, it can be easy to lose track of which one you are
        are trying to solve for.
        <md>
          <mrow>P\amp=\attention{R}-C</mrow>
          <mrow>P\addright{C}\amp=\attention{R}-C\addright{C}</mrow>
          <mrow>P+C\amp=\attention{R}\amp\implies R=P+C</mrow>
        </md>
        In other words, revenue is the sum of profit and cost.
      </p>
    </example>

    <example xml:id="example-solve-for-variable-slope-intercept">
      <statement>
        <p>
          Solve for <m>x</m> in <m>y=mx+b</m>. (This is a line's equation in slope-intercept form,
          which we study thoroughly in <xref ref="section-slope"/>.)
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          In the equation <m>y=mx+b</m>, we see that <m>x</m> is multiplied by <m>m</m> and then
          <m>b</m> is added to that. Think of <m>x</m> as a birthday present, enclosed in a box, and
          then placed in a gift bag. To get your gift, you need to <q>undo</q> those containers in
          the opposite order: take it out of the bag, then open the box. We need to undo multiplying
          by <m>m</m> and adding <m>b</m> in the opposite order. So we will start by subtracting
          <m>b</m>:
          <md>
            <mrow>y\amp=m\attention{x}+b</mrow>
            <mrow>y\subtractright{b}\amp=m\attention{x}+b\subtractright{b}</mrow>
            <mrow>y-b\amp=m\attention{x}</mrow>
          </md>
          And then dividing by <m>m</m>:
          <md>
            <mrow>\divideunder{y-b}{m}\amp=\divideunder{m\attention{x}}{m}</mrow>
            <mrow>\frac{y-b}{m}\amp=\attention{x}\amp\implies x\amp=\frac{y-b}{m}</mrow>
          </md>
        </p>
      </solution>
    </example>

    <warning>
      <p>
        In <xref ref="example-solve-for-variable-slope-intercept"/>, each <em>side</em> was divided
        by <m>m</m>. It's not uncommon for students to have <m>y-b=mx</m> and write something like
        <m>\frac{y}{m}-b=\frac{mx}{m}</m>, but this is incorrect. If you are going to divide by
        something as a step in the process, you will need to divide the two <em>sides</em> of the
        equation, not just parts within those sides.
      </p>
    </warning>

    <example>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Solve for <m>b</m> in <m>A=\frac{1}{2}bh</m>. (This is the area formula for a triangle.)
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          When an equation has fractions, a helpful first step is to clear denominators. So here we
          will multiply by <m>2</m> on each side.
          <md>
            <mrow>\multiplyleft{2}A\amp=\multiplyleft{2}\frac{1}{2}\attention{b}h</mrow>
            <mrow>2A\amp=\attention{b}h</mrow>
          </md>
          Now our target variable is being multiplied by <m>h</m>, so we apply the opposite action,
          dividing by <m>h</m>:
          <md>
            <mrow>\divideunder{2A}{h}\amp=\divideunder{\attention{b}h}{h}</mrow>
            <mrow>\frac{2A}{h}\amp=\attention{b}\amp\implies b\amp=\frac{2A}{h}</mrow>
          </md>
        </p>
      </solution>
    </example>

    <exercise label="solve-for-variable-standard-form" xml:id="exercise-solve-for-variable-standard-form">
      <webwork>
        <pg-code>
          Context("Numeric")->variables->add(y=>'Real');
          parser::Assignment->Allow;
          $answer = Formula("y=(10-2x)/5");
        </pg-code>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Solve for <m>y</m> in <m>2x+5y=10</m>.
          </p>
          <p>
            <var name="$answer" width="20"/>
          </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
          <p>
            To solve for <m>y</m>, we first isolate <m>5y</m> by subtracting <m>2x</m> from each
            side of the equation. After that, we can divide each side by <m>5</m> to finish solving
            for <m>y</m>:
            <md>
              <mrow>2x+5\attention{y}\amp=10</mrow>
              <mrow>2x+5\attention{y}\subtractright{2x}\amp=10\subtractright{2x}</mrow>
              <mrow>5\attention{y}\amp=10-2x</mrow>
              <mrow>\divideunder{5\attention{y}}{5}\amp=\divideunder{10-2x}{5}</mrow>
              <mrow>y\amp=\frac{10-2x}{5}</mrow>
            </md>
          </p>
        </solution>
      </webwork>
    </exercise>

    <example xml:id="example-solve-for-variable-celsius-fahrenheit">
      <statement>
        <p>
          Solve for <m>F</m> in <m>C=\frac{5}{9}(F-32)</m>. (This represents the relationship
          between temperature in degrees Celsius and degrees Fahrenheit.)
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          There is more than one way to do this, but we will start by clearing the denominator:
          <md>
            <mrow>C\amp=\frac{5}{9}(\attention{F}-32)</mrow>
            <mrow>\multiplyleft{9}C\amp=\multiplyleft{9}\frac{5}{9}(\attention{F}-32)</mrow>
            <mrow>9C\amp=5(\attention{F}-32)</mrow>
          </md>
          Now what is happening to our target variable <m>F</m>? It has <m>32</m> subtracted from
          it, and then that result is multiplied by <m>5</m>. So we will do the opposite actions in
          the opposite order: divide by <m>5</m> and then add <m>32</m>.
          <md>
            <mrow>\divideunder{9C}{5}\amp=\divideunder{5(\attention{F}-32)}{5}</mrow>
            <mrow>\frac{9C}{5}\amp=\attention{F}-32</mrow>
            <mrow>\frac{9C}{5}\addright{32}\amp=\attention{F}-32\addright{32}</mrow>
            <mrow>\frac{9C}{5}+32\amp=\attention{F}\amp\implies F\amp=\frac{9}{5}C+32</mrow>
          </md>
        </p>
      </solution>
    </example>
  </subsection>

  <subsection>
    <title>Clearing Denominators</title>

    <p>
      Consider an equation with fractions present in the coefficients or terms, for example:                  <idx><h>Equation(s)</h><h>with fractions</h></idx>
      <md>\frac{1}{4}x+\frac{2}{3}=\frac{1}{6}</md>                                                           <idx><h>Fraction</h><h>linear equations with</h></idx>
      We could solve this using the same steps from earlier in this section, but we'd have to do              <idx><h>Linear equations</h><h>with fractions</h></idx>
      some fraction subtraction, followed by some fraction division. In other words, we'd need to do
      fraction arithmetic, which ismore likely to lead to human error than whole number arithmetic.
    </p>
    <p>
      An alternative is to multiply each side of the equation by a helpful number that <q>clears</q>          <idx><h>Fraction</h><h>clearing denominators</h></idx>
      the denominator(s). In the above example, the helpful number would be <m>12</m>:
      <md>
        <mrow>\frac{1}{4}x+\frac{2}{3}\amp=\frac{1}{6}</mrow>
        <mrow>\multiplyleft{12}\left(\frac{1}{4}x+\frac{2}{3}\right)\amp=\multiplyleft{12}\left(\frac{1}{6}\right)</mrow>
        <mrow>3x+8\amp=2</mrow>
      </md>
      Somehow multiplying by <m>12</m> cleared all of the fractions from the equation. We could
      solve this equation easily now. This section covers this technique, which generally makes it
      easier to solve linear equations and inequalities when fractions are present.
    </p>

    <figure>
      <caption>Alternative Video Lessons</caption>
      <video youtubeplaylist="PLmuZCPhWPt-e_QSbGeacmrdYyommPaxf4" />
    </figure>

    <example>
      <sidebyside widths="47% 47%" margins="0%">
        <stack>
          <p>
            Deshawn planted a sapling in his yard that was
            <quantity><mag>4</mag><unit base="foot"/></quantity> tall. The tree will grow
            <m>\frac{2}{3}</m> of a foot every year. How many years will it take for his tree to
            become <quantity><mag>10</mag><unit base="foot"/></quantity> tall?
          </p>

          <p>
            We can use a table to help understand the rate of growth and then write a formula that
            models the tree's growth:
          </p>
        </stack>

        <tabular>
          <col halign="center"/>
          <col halign="left"/>
          <row bottom="medium" header="yes">
            <cell>Years Passed</cell>
            <cell>Tree's Height (ft)</cell>
          </row>
          <row>
            <cell><m>0</m></cell>
            <cell><m>4</m></cell>
          </row>
          <row>
            <cell><m>1</m></cell>
            <cell><m>4+\frac{2}{3}</m></cell>
          </row>
          <row>
            <cell><m>2</m></cell>
            <cell><m>4+\frac{2}{3}\cdot2</m></cell>
          </row>
          <row>
            <cell><m>3</m></cell>
            <cell><m>4+\frac{2}{3}\cdot3</m></cell>
          </row>
          <row>
            <cell><m>\vdots</m></cell>
            <cell><m>\vdots</m></cell>
          </row>
          <row>
            <cell><m>y</m></cell>
            <cell><m>4+\frac{2}{3}y</m></cell>
          </row>
        </tabular>

      </sidebyside>

      <p>
        We find that <m>y</m> years since the tree was planted, the tree's height is
        <m>4+\frac{2}{3}y</m> feet. To find when Deshawn's tree will be <m>10</m> feet tall, we set
        up the equation
        <md>4+\frac{2}{3}y=10</md>
        Note that the equation has a fraction present as a coefficient.
      </p>

      <p>
        To solve the equation, note that the fraction's denominator is <m>3</m>. As the very first
        step, multiplying by <m>3</m> on each side of the equation will leave us with no
        fractions.
        <md>
          <mrow>4+\frac{2}{3}y\amp=10</mrow>
          <mrow>\multiplyleft{3}\left(4+\frac{2}{3}y\right)\amp=\multiplyleft{3}10</mrow>
          <mrow>3\cdot4+3\cdot\frac{2}{3}y\amp=30</mrow>
          <mrow>12+2y\amp=30\amp\text{(it's smooth sailing from here)}</mrow>
          <mrow>2y\amp=18</mrow>
          <mrow>y\amp=9</mrow>
        </md>
      </p>

      <p>
        Let's check the solution <m>9</m> to be sure:
        <md>
          <mrow>4+\frac{2}{3}y\amp=10</mrow>
          <mrow>4+\frac{2}{3}(\substitute{9})\amp\wonder{=}10</mrow>
          <mrow>4+6\amp\confirm{=}10</mrow>
        </md>
      </p>

      <p>
        In summary, it will take <m>9</m> years for Deshawn's tree to reach <m>10</m> feet tall. The
        point of this example was to demonstrate how clearing denominators can make an equation
        relatively easier to solve.
      </p>
    </example>

    <exercise label="water-evaporating">
      <webwork>
        <pg-macros>
          <macro-file>parserLinearRelation.pl</macro-file>
        </pg-macros>
        <pg-code>
          Context("LinearRelation");
          Context()->variables->are(t => "Real");
          Context()->operators->undefine("/");
          Parser::Number::NoDecimals();
          $equation = Formula("105-3t=40");
        </pg-code>
        <statement>
          <p>
            In a science lab, a container had <m>21</m> ounces of water at 9:00<nbsp/><am/>. Water
            has been evaporating at the rate of <m>3</m> ounces every <m>5</m> minutes. When will
            there be <m>8</m> ounces of water left?
          </p>
          <instruction>
            Write an equation for this scenario, using <m>t</m> as the variable. Then do what is
            needed to clear the denominators. Enter the equation with cleared denominators.
          </instruction>
          <p>
            <var name="$equation" width="16"/>
          </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
          <p>
            Since the container has been losing <m>3</m> oz of water every <m>5</m> minutes, it
            loses <m>\frac{3}{5}</m> oz every minute. At <m>t</m> minutes past 9:00<nbsp/><am/>, the
            container will have lost <m>\frac{3}{5}t</m> oz of water. Since the initial amount was
            <m>21</m> oz, the amount of water in the container (in oz) can be modeled by
            <m>21-\frac{3}{5}t</m>.
          </p>
          <p>
            So to work out when there would be only <m>8</m> oz of water left, we write the
            following equation. Note there is a denominator of <m>5</m>, which we can clear.
            <md>
              <mrow>21-\frac{3}{5}t\amp=8</mrow>
              <mrow>\multiplyleft{5}\left(21-\frac{3}{5}t\right)\amp=\multiplyleft{5}8</mrow>
              <mrow>5\cdot21-5\cdot\frac{3}{5}t\amp=40</mrow>
              <mrow>105-3t\amp=40</mrow>
            </md>
          </p>
          <p>
            From here it is straightforward to use steps from
            <xref ref="section-linear-equations-and-inequalities"/> to solve the equation. You can
            try that on your own and you should find that it will take between <m>21</m> and
            <m>22</m> minutes for the container to only have <m>8</m> ounces of water left.
          </p>
        </solution>
      </webwork>
    </exercise>

    <p>
      The previous examples only had one fraction in the equation. What happens if there are more?
    </p>

    <example>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Solve for <m>x</m> in <m>\frac{1}{4}x+\frac{2}{3}=\frac{1}{6}</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          Once again, we have an equation with fractions present. This time there are multiple
          denominators: <m>4</m>, <m>3</m>, and <m>6</m>. Is there <em>one</em> number we could use
          to clear all three denominators? The <q>Least Common Multiple</q> of the denominators
          (abbreviated as LCM or LCD) would work. Anything that is a multiple of all three of these
          denominators would work, and using the smallest such number is just a good habit. In this
          case, the LCD is <m>12</m>. So we will multiply each side of the equation by <m>12</m>:
        </p>

        <sidebyside widths="47% 47%" margins="0%">
          <p>
            <md>
              <mrow>\frac{1}{4}x+\frac{2}{3}\amp=\frac{1}{6}</mrow>
              <mrow>\multiplyleft{12}\left(\frac{1}{4}x+\frac{2}{3}\right)\amp=\multiplyleft{12}\frac{1}{6}</mrow>
              <mrow>12\cdot\left(\frac{1}{4}x\right)+12\cdot\left(\frac{2}{3}\right)\amp=12\cdot\frac{1}{6}</mrow>
              <mrow>3x+8\amp=2</mrow>
              <mrow>3x\amp=-6</mrow>
              <mrow>x\amp=-2</mrow>
            </md>
          </p>

          <p>
            Checking the solution <m>-2</m>:
            <md>
              <mrow>\frac{1}{4}x+\frac{2}{3}\amp=\frac{1}{6}</mrow>
              <mrow>\frac{1}{4}(\substitute{-2})+\frac{2}{3}\amp\wonder{=}\frac{1}{6}</mrow>
              <mrow>-\frac{2}{4}+\frac{2}{3}\amp\wonder{=}\frac{1}{6}</mrow>
              <mrow>-\frac{6}{12}+\frac{8}{12}\amp\wonder{=}\frac{1}{6}</mrow>
              <mrow>\frac{2}{12}\amp\confirm{=}\frac{1}{6}</mrow>
            </md>
          </p>
        </sidebyside>

        <p>
          The solution is therefore <m>-2</m> and the solution set is <m>\{-2\}</m>.
        </p>
      </solution>
    </example>

    <exercise label="solve-by-clearing-denominator">
      <webwork>
        <pg-code>
          Context("FiniteSolutionSets");
          Context()->variables->are(z => 'Real');
          $solution = Formula("{23}");
        </pg-code>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Solve for <m>z</m> in <m>-\frac{2}{5}z-\frac{3}{2}=-\frac{1}{2}z+\frac{4}{5}</m>.
          </p>
          <p>
            <var name="$solution" width="20"/>
          </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
          <p>
            With fractions present, we decide to identify the LCD. The denominators are <m>2</m> and
            <m>5</m>, so the LCD is <m>10</m>. And so our first algebra step is to multiply each
            side of the equation by <m>10</m>:
            <md>
              <mrow>-\frac{2}{5}z-\frac{3}{2}\amp=-\frac{1}{2}z+\frac{4}{5}</mrow>
              <mrow>\multiplyleft{10}\left(-\frac{2}{5}z-\frac{3}{2}\right)\amp=\multiplyleft{10}\left(-\frac{1}{2}z+\frac{4}{5}\right)</mrow>
              <mrow>10\left(-\frac{2}{5}z\right)-10\left(\frac{3}{2}\right)\amp=10\left(-\frac{1}{2}z\right)+10\left(\frac{4}{5}\right)</mrow>
              <mrow>-4z-15\amp=-5z+8</mrow>
              <mrow>z-15\amp=8</mrow>
              <mrow>z\amp=23</mrow>
            </md>
          </p>

          <p>
            Checking the solution <m>23</m>:
            <md>
              <mrow>-\frac{2}{5}z-\frac{3}{2}\amp=-\frac{1}{2}z+\frac{4}{5}</mrow>
              <mrow>-\frac{2}{5}(\substitute{23})-\frac{3}{2}\amp\wonder{=}-\frac{1}{2}(\substitute{23})+\frac{4}{5}</mrow>
              <mrow>-\frac{46}{5}-\frac{3}{2}\amp\wonder{=}-\frac{23}{2}+\frac{4}{5}</mrow>
              <mrow>-\frac{92}{10}-\frac{15}{10}\amp\wonder{=}-\frac{115}{10}+\frac{8}{10}</mrow>
              <mrow>-\frac{107}{10}\amp\confirm{=}-\frac{107}{10}</mrow>
            </md>
          </p>

          <p>
            So the solution is <m>23</m> and so the solution set is <m>\{23\}</m>.
          </p>
        </solution>
      </webwork>
    </exercise>

    <example>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Solve for <m>a</m> in the equation <m>\frac{2}{3}(a+1)+5=\frac{1}{3}</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          There are two fractions appearing here, and both have the same denominator <m>3</m>.
          We can multiply by <m>3</m> on each side and that alone will clear the denominators.
        </p>
        <sidebyside widths="47% 47%" margins="0%">
          <p>
            <md>
              <mrow>\frac{2}{3}(a+1)+5\amp=\frac{1}{3}</mrow>
              <mrow>\multiplyleft{3}\left(\frac{2}{3}(a+1)+5\right)\amp=\multiplyleft{3}\frac{1}{3}</mrow>
              <mrow>2(a+1)+15\amp=1</mrow>
              <mrow>2a+2+15\amp=1</mrow>
              <mrow>2a+17\amp=1</mrow>
              <mrow>2a\amp=-16</mrow>
              <mrow>a\amp=-8</mrow>
            </md>
          </p>

          <p>
            Checking the solution <m>-8</m>:
            <md>
              <mrow>\frac{2}{3}(a+1)+5\amp=\frac{1}{3}</mrow>
              <mrow>\frac{2}{3}(\substitute{-8}+1)+5\amp\wonder{=}\frac{1}{3}</mrow>
              <mrow>\frac{2}{3}(-7)+5\amp\wonder{=}\frac{1}{3}</mrow>
              <mrow>-\frac{14}{3}+\frac{15}{3}\amp\confirm{=}\frac{1}{3}</mrow>
            </md>
          </p>
        </sidebyside>

        <p>
          The solution is therefore <m>-8</m> and the solution set is <m>\{-8\}</m>.
        </p>
      </solution>
    </example>

    <example xml:id="example-cross-multiply-showing-LCD">
      <statement>
        <p>
          Solve for <m>b</m> in the equation <m>\frac{2b+1}{3}=\frac{2}{5}</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          The structure of the equation is a little different from previous examples, but we can
          still see that there are denominators <m>3</m> and <m>5</m>, and that their LCM is
          <m>15</m>. Multiplying each side of the equation by <m>15</m> will help.
        </p>
        <sidebyside widths="47% 47%" margins="0%">
          <p>
            <md>
              <mrow>\frac{2b+1}{3}\amp=\frac{2}{5}</mrow>
              <mrow>\multiplyleft{15}\frac{2b+1}{3}\amp=\multiplyleft{15}\frac{2}{5}</mrow>
              <mrow>5(2b+1)\amp=6</mrow>
              <mrow>10b+5\amp=6</mrow>
              <mrow>10b\amp=1</mrow>
              <mrow>b\amp=\frac{1}{10}</mrow>
            </md>
          </p>
          <p>
            Checking the solution <m>\frac{1}{10}</m>:
            <md>
              <!-- <mrow>\frac{2b+1}{3}\amp=\frac{2}{5}</mrow> -->
              <mrow>\frac{2\left(\substitute{\frac{1}{10}}\right)+1}{3}\amp\wonder{=}\frac{2}{5}</mrow>
              <mrow>\frac{\frac{1}{5}+1}{3}\amp\wonder{=}\frac{2}{5}</mrow>
              <!-- <mrow>\frac{\frac{1}{5}+\frac{5}{5}}{3}\amp\wonder{=}\frac{2}{5}</mrow> -->
              <mrow>\frac{\frac{6}{5}}{3}\amp\wonder{=}\frac{2}{5}</mrow>
              <mrow>\frac{6}{5}\cdot \frac{1}{3}\amp\confirm{=}\frac{2}{5}</mrow>
            </md>
          </p>
        </sidebyside>

        <p>
          The solution is <m>\frac{1}{10}</m> and the solution set is
          <m>\left\{\frac{1}{10}\right\}</m>.
        </p>
      </solution>
    </example>

    <p>
      In <xref ref="section-modeling-with-equations-and-inequalities"/>, we investigated some
      proportional equations, but did not solve them. Now we can clear denominators to make it a bit
      easier to solve them.
    </p>

    <p>
      Let's revisit <xref ref="example-proportion-in-price"/>.
    </p>

    <example>
      <p>
        Suppose we know the cost of a <m>21</m>-ounce box of cereal, and we want to know the cost of
        and <m>18</m>-ounce box assuming that it costs the same per ounce. Letting <m>C</m> be this
        unknown cost (in dollars), we could set up a proportional equation. Whether we are dealing
        with the smaller box or the larger box, the ratio of cost to weight is supposed to be the
        same. So in the following equation on the left, we enter details for the larger box. And on
        the right, for the smaller box.
        <md>
          <mrow>\frac{\text{cost in dollars}}{\text{weight in oz}}\amp=\frac{\text{cost in dollars}}{\text{weight in oz}}</mrow>
          <mrow>\frac{\$3.99}{21\,\text{oz}}\amp=\frac{\$C}{18\,\text{oz}}</mrow>
        </md>
        We can rewrite this equation without the units:
        <md>
          \frac{3.99}{21}=\frac{C}{18}
        </md>
        And we have an equation with fractions present. We want to multiply each side by the LCD,
        but this time the denominators are larger than previous examples. Can we still find the LCD?
        We could! But it is maybe not worth the time and effort. Having the <em>least</em> common
        multiple is a nice thing, but <em>any</em> common multiple of denominators will work out for
        our needs. A simple way to get a common multiple is just to multiply the numbers together.
        So we choose to multiply each side by <m>18\cdot 21</m> instead of whatever the actual LCD
        is.
        <md>
          <mrow>\frac{3.99}{21}\amp=\frac{C}{18}</mrow>
          <mrow>\multiplyleft{18\cdot21}\frac{3.99}{21}\amp=\multiplyleft{18\cdot21}\frac{3.99}{21}\frac{C}{18}</mrow>
          <mrow>18\cdot\cancelhighlight{21}\cdot\frac{3.99}{\cancelhighlight{21}}\amp=\cancelhighlight{18}\cdot21\cdot\frac{C}{\cancelhighlight{18}}</mrow>
          <mrow>71.82\amp=21C</mrow>
          <mrow>\divideunder{71.82}{21}\amp=\divideunder{21C}{21}</mrow>
          <mrow>C\amp=3.42</mrow>
        </md>
        So assuming the cost is proportional to the cost of the <m>21</m>-ounce box, the cost for an
        <m>18</m>-ounce box of cereal would be <m>\$3.42</m>.
      </p>
    </example>

    <p>
      Now let's revisit <xref ref="example-proportion-in-taxes"/>.
    </p>

    <example>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Property taxes for a residential property are proportional to the assessed value of the
          property. A certain home is assessed at <m>\$234{,}100</m> and its annual property taxes
          are <m>\$2{,}518.92</m>. Set up an equation to find the annual property taxes for the
          house next door that is assessed at <m>\$287{,}500</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          Let <m>T</m> be the annual property taxes (in dollars) for a property assessed at
          <m>\$287{,}500</m>. We can write and solve this proportion:
          <md>
            <mrow>\frac{\text{tax}}{\text{property value}}\amp=\frac{\text{tax}}{\text{property value}}</mrow>
            <mrow>\frac{2518.92}{234100}\amp=\frac{T}{287500}</mrow>
          </md>
          The least common denominator of this proportion is rather large, so we will instead
          multiply each side by <m>234100</m> and <m>287500</m> and simplify from there:
          <md>
            <mrow>\frac{2518.92}{234100}\amp=\frac{T}{287500}</mrow>
            <mrow>\multiplyleft{234100\cdot287500}\cdot\frac{2518.92}{234100}\amp=\multiplyleft{234100\cdot287500}\cdot\frac{T}{287500}</mrow>
            <mrow>287500\cdot2518.92 \amp=234100T </mrow>
            <mrow>\frac{287500\cdot 2518.92}{234100} \amp=\frac{234100T}{234100}</mrow>
            <mrow>T\amp\approx3093.50</mrow>
          </md>
          The property taxes for a property assessed at
          <m>\$287{,}500</m> are <m>\$3{,}093.50</m>.
        </p>
      </solution>
    </example>

    <exercise label="tylenol-proportion-solved">
      <webwork>
          <pg-code>
            $newUnits = [
              {name=>'mL',conversion=>{factor=>1E-6,m=>3}},
              {name=>'ml',conversion=>{factor=>1E-6,m=>3}},
              {name=>'milliliters',conversion=>{factor=>1E-6,m=>3}},
              {name=>'milliliter',conversion=>{factor=>1E-6,m=>3}},
              {name=>'cc',conversion=>{factor=>1E-6,m=>3}},
            ];
            $answer = NumberWithUnits("1.875 mL", {newUnit=>$newUnits});
          </pg-code>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Infant Tylenol contains
            <quantity>
              <mag>160</mag><unit prefix="milli" base="gram"/>
            </quantity>
            of acetaminophen in each
            <quantity>
              <mag>5</mag><unit prefix="milli" base="liter"/>
            </quantity>
            of liquid.
            If Bao's baby is prescribed
            <quantity>
              <mag>60</mag><unit prefix="milli" base="gram"/>
            </quantity>
            of acetaminophen,
            how many milliliters of liquid should he give the baby?
          </p>
          <p>
            <var name="$answer" width="10"/>
          </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
          <p>
            Assume Bao should give <m>q</m> milliliters of liquid medicine,
            so we can set up the following proportion:
            <md>
              <mrow>\frac{\text{amount of liquid medicine in mL}}{\text{amount of acetaminophen in mg}}\amp=\frac{\text{amount of liquid medicine in mL}}{\text{amount of acetaminophen in mg}}</mrow>
              <mrow>\frac{5\,\text{mL}}{160\,\text{mg}}\amp=\frac{q\,\text{mL}}{60\,\text{mg}}</mrow>
              <mrow>\frac{5}{160}\amp=\frac{q}{60}</mrow>
              <mrow>\multiplyleft{160\cdot 60}\cdot\frac{5}{160}\amp=\multiplyleft{160\cdot 60}\cdot\frac{q}{60}</mrow>
              <mrow>300\amp=160q</mrow>
              <mrow>\divideunder{300}{160}\amp=\divideunder{160q}{160}</mrow>
              <mrow>q\amp=1.875</mrow>
            </md>
            So to give
            <quantity>
              <mag>60</mag><unit prefix="milli" base="gram"/>
            </quantity>
            of acetaminophen to his baby, Bao should measure out
            <quantity>
              <mag>1.875</mag><unit prefix="milli" base="liter"/>
            </quantity>
            of the liquid medication.
          </p>
        </solution>
      </webwork>
    </exercise>

    <p>
      The technique of clearing denominators also applies to inequalities, not just equations.
    </p>

    <example>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Solve for <m>x</m> in the inequality <m>\frac{3}{4}x-2\gt\frac{4}{5}x</m>. Write the
          solution set in both set-builder notation and interval notation.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          The LCM of the denominators is <m>20</m>, so we start out multiplying each side of the
          inequality by <m>20</m>.
          <md>
            <mrow>\frac{3}{4}x-2\amp\gt\frac{4}{5}x</mrow>
            <mrow>\multiplyleft{20}\left(\frac{3}{4}x-2\right)\amp\gt\multiplyleft{20}\frac{4}{5}x</mrow>
            <mrow>20\cdot\frac{3}{4}x-20\cdot2\amp\gt16x</mrow>
            <mrow>15x-40\amp\gt16x</mrow>
            <mrow>-40\amp\gt x</mrow>
            <mrow>x\amp\lt-40</mrow>
          </md>
        </p>

        <p>
          The solution set in set-builder notation is <m>\{x\mid x\lt-40\}</m>. And in interval
          notation, it's <m>(-\infty,-40)</m>.
        </p>
      </solution>
    </example>

    <exercise label="inequality-with-clearing-denominators">
      <webwork>
        <pg-code>
          Context("Interval");
          Context()->flags->set(reduceConstants=>0);
          $in = Interval("[-1/14,inf)");
          InequalitySetBuilder::UseVerticalSuchThat();
          Context("InequalitySetBuilder-Only");
          Context()->flags->set(reduceConstants=>0);
          $sb = Compute("{ x | x >= -1/14}");
        </pg-code>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Solve for <m>x</m> in the inequality <m>\frac{4}{7}-\frac{4}{3}x\le\frac{2}{3}</m>.
            Write the solution set in both set-builder notation and interval notation.
          </p>
          <instruction>
            In set-builder notation:
          </instruction>
          <p>
            <var name="$sb" width="20"/>
          </p>
          <instruction>
            In interval notation:
          </instruction>
          <p>
            <var name="$in" width="20"/>
          </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
          <p>
            The LCM of the denominators is <m>21</m>, so we start out by multiplying each side of
            the inequality by <m>21</m>.
            <md>
              <mrow>\frac{4}{7}-\frac{4}{3}x\amp\le\frac{2}{3}</mrow>
              <mrow>\multiplyleft{21}\left(\frac{4}{7}-\frac{4}{3}x\right)\amp\le\multiplyleft{21}\left(\frac{2}{3}\right)</mrow>
              <mrow>21\left(\frac{4}{7}\right)-21\left(\frac{4}{3}x\right)\amp\le21\left(\frac{2}{3}\right)</mrow>
              <mrow>12-28x\amp\le14</mrow>
              <mrow>-28x\amp\le2</mrow>
              <mrow>\divideunder{-28x}{-28}\amp\secondhighlight{{}\ge{}}\divideunder{2}{-28}</mrow>
              <mrow>x\amp\ge-\frac{1}{14}</mrow>
            </md>
          </p>

          <p>
            Note that when we divided each side of the inequality by <m>-28</m>, the inequality
            symbol reversed direction. The solution set in set-builder notation is
            <m>\left\{x\mid x\ge-\frac{1}{14}\right\}</m>. The solution set in interval notation is
            <m>\left[-\frac{1}{14},\infty\right)</m>.
          </p>
        </solution>
      </webwork>
    </exercise>
  </subsection>

  <reading-questions>
    <exercise label="steps-to-solve-linear-equation">
      <statement>
        <p>
          Describe the five steps you might need to take when solving a linear equation.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <response/>
    </exercise>
    <exercise label="care-with-distributing-negative">
      <statement>
        <p>
          In this section there is a reminder to take care with negative numbers when doing what?
        </p>
      </statement>
      <response/>
    </exercise>
    <!-- <exercise label="solving-vocabulary-misuse">
      <statement>
        <p>
          Explain what is wrong with saying <q>I need to solve <m>3x+x-8</m>.</q>
        </p>
      </statement>
      <response/>
    </exercise> -->
    <exercise label="when-reverse-direction">
      <statement>
        <p>
          When solving an inequality, what are the conditions when you have to reverse the direction
          of the inequality symbol?
        </p>
      </statement>
      <response/>
    </exercise>
    <exercise label="differences-in-solution-sets">
      <statement>
        <p>
          How is the solution set to a linear inequality different from the solution set to a linear
          equation?
        </p>
      </statement>
      <response/>
    </exercise>
    <exercise label="how-to-check-solution-to-inequality">
      <statement>
        <p>
          If you want to check your solution set to a linear inequality, what exactly are you going
          to do?
        </p>
      </statement>
      <response/>
    </exercise>
    <exercise label="how-many-solutions-including-special">
      <statement>
        <p>
          With a linear equation in one variable, what are the possibilities for how many solutions
          it could have? One solution? Two solutions? Are there other possibilities?
        </p>
      </statement>
      <response/>
    </exercise>
    <exercise label="how-do-you-know-no-solution">
      <statement>
        <p>
          How will you know when a linear equation or inequality has no solution?
        </p>
      </statement>
      <response/>
    </exercise>
    <exercise label="how-do-you-know-all-are-solutions">
      <statement>
        <p>
          How will you know when all numbers are solutions to a linear equation or inequality?
        </p>
      </statement>
      <response/>
    </exercise>
    <exercise label="divide-only-some-terms">
      <statement>
        <p>
          Suppose you want to solve the equation <m>mq+b=T</m> for <m>q</m>. What would be wrong
          with dividing on each side by <m>m</m> to get <m>\frac{mq}{m}+b=\frac{T}{m}</m>?
        </p>
      </statement>
      <response/>
    </exercise>
    <exercise label="undo-dividing-by-R">
      <statement>
        <p>
          How do you undo dividing something by <m>R</m>?
        </p>
      </statement>
      <response/>
    </exercise>
    <exercise label="why-solve-for-a-variable">
      <statement>
        <p>
          Why we might we want to take a formula like <m>P=IV</m> and isolate <m>I</m>, writing the
          equation as <m>I=\frac{P}{V}</m>?
        </p>
      </statement>
      <response/>
    </exercise>
    <exercise label="what-does-lcd-stand-for">
      <statement>
        <p>
          What does LCD stand for? And using different words, explain what it is.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <response/>
    </exercise>
    <exercise label="multiply-which-two-things">
      <statement>
        <p>
          When you clear denominators from an equation like <m>\frac{2}{3}x+5=\frac{2}{7}</m>, you
          will multiply by <m>21</m>. What are the <em>two</em> things that you multiply by
          <m>21</m>? Hint: it is not the two fractions.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <response/>
    </exercise>
    <exercise label="what-is-a-proportional-equation">
      <statement>
        <p>
          What is a proportional equation?
        </p>
      </statement>
      <response/>
    </exercise>
  </reading-questions>

  <exercises>
    <subexercises>
      <title>Review and Warmup</title>
      <exercisegroup cols="3">
        <title>One-Step Equations</title>
        <introduction>
          <p>
            Solve the equation.
          </p>
        </introduction>
        <exercise label="solve-equation-add-right-integer-copy3">
          <webwork copy="webwork-solve-equation-add-right-integer"/>
        </exercise>
        <exercise label="solve-equation-divide-integer-copy3">
          <webwork copy="webwork-solve-equation-divide-integer"/>
        </exercise>
        <exercise label="solve-equation-negate-integer-copy3">
          <webwork copy="webwork-solve-equation-negate-integer"/>
        </exercise>
        <exercise label="solve-equation-add-left-fraction-copy3">
          <webwork copy="webwork-solve-equation-add-left-fraction"/>
        </exercise>
        <exercise label="solve-equation-negate-fraction-copy3">
          <webwork copy="webwork-solve-equation-negate-fraction"/>
        </exercise>
        <exercise label="solve-equation-add-left-decimal-copy3">
          <webwork copy="webwork-solve-equation-add-left-decimal"/>
        </exercise>
      </exercisegroup>
      <exercisegroup cols="4">
        <title>One-Step Inequalities</title>
        <introduction>
          <p>
            Solve the inequality.
          </p>
        </introduction>
        <exercise label="solve-inequality-add-right-integer">
          <webwork xml:id="webwork-solve-inequality-add-right-integer">
            <pg-macros>
              <macro-file>parserGraphTool.pl</macro-file>
            </pg-macros>
            <pg-code>
              $var = list_random('a'..'n','p'..'z','A'..'D', 'F'..'N','P'..'T','V'..'Z');
              Context()->variables->are($var => 'Real');
              $c = random(-6,6);
              $a = random(1,20);
              $b = $a + $c;
              $left = Formula("$var + $a")->reduce;
              $right = Formula("$b")->reduce;
              $sign = list_random('\lt', '\gt', '\leq', '\geq');
              %interval = (
                '\lt'  => "(-inf, $c)",
                '\gt'  => "($c, inf)",
                '\leq' => "(-inf, $c]",
                '\geq' => "[$c, inf)"
              );
              Context("Interval");
              $interval = Interval($interval{$sign});
              InequalitySetBuilder::UseVerticalSuchThat();
              Context("InequalitySetBuilder-Only");
              Context()->variables->are($var => 'Real');
              %perlsign = (
                '\lt'  => "&lt;",
                '\gt'  => ">",
                '\leq' => "&lt;=",
                '\geq' => ">="
              );
              $perlsign = $perlsign{$sign};
              $setbuilder = Compute("{ $var | $var $perlsign $c}");
              $gt = GraphTool("{interval, $interval}")->with(
                availableTools => ['IntervalTool', 'IncludeExcludePointTool'],
                numberLine => 1,
                xAxisLabel => "$var",
                bBox => [ -8, 8 ],
                ticksDistanceX => 1,
                minorTicksX => 0,
                useBracketEnds => 1,
                showInStatic => 0,
                showCoordinateHints => 0,
              );
            </pg-code>
            <statement>
              <p>
                <m><var name="$left"/><var name="$sign"/><var name="$right"/></m>
              </p>
              <p>
                <var name="$gt" width="1"/>
              </p>
              <instruction>
                In interval notation.
              </instruction>
              <p>
                <var name="$interval" width="12"/>
              </p>
              <instruction>
                In set-builder notation. (If needed, type <c>inf</c> or <c>infinity</c>
                for <m>\infty</m>, <c>&gt;=</c> for <m>\geq</m>, and <c>&lt;=</c> for <m>\leq</m>.)
              </instruction>
              <p>
                <var name="$setbuilder" width="12"/>
              </p>
            </statement>
          </webwork>
        </exercise>
        <exercise label="solve-inequality-multiply-integer">
          <webwork xml:id="webwork-solve-inequality-multiply-integer">
            <pg-macros>
              <macro-file>parserGraphTool.pl</macro-file>
            </pg-macros>
            <pg-code>
              $var = list_random('a'..'n','p'..'z','A'..'D', 'F'..'N','P'..'T','V'..'Z');
              Context()->variables->are($var => 'Real');
              $c = non_zero_random(-6,6);
              $a = random(2,20);
              $b = $a*$c;
              $left = Formula("$a $var")->reduce;
              $right = Formula("$b")->reduce;
              $sign = list_random('\lt', '\gt', '\leq', '\geq');
              %interval = (
                '\lt'  => "(-inf, $c)",
                '\gt'  => "($c, inf)",
                '\leq' => "(-inf, $c]",
                '\geq' => "[$c, inf)"
              );
              Context("Interval");
              $interval = Interval($interval{$sign});
              InequalitySetBuilder::UseVerticalSuchThat();
              Context("InequalitySetBuilder-Only");
              Context()->variables->are($var => 'Real');
              %perlsign = (
                '\lt'  => "&lt;",
                '\gt'  => ">",
                '\leq' => "&lt;=",
                '\geq' => ">="
              );
              $perlsign = $perlsign{$sign};
              $setbuilder = Compute("{ $var | $var $perlsign $c}");
              $gt = GraphTool("{interval, $interval}")->with(
                availableTools => ['IntervalTool', 'IncludeExcludePointTool'],
                numberLine => 1,
                xAxisLabel => "$var",
                bBox => [ -8, 8 ],
                ticksDistanceX => 1,
                minorTicksX => 0,
                useBracketEnds => 1,
                showInStatic => 0,
                showCoordinateHints => 0,
              );
              %words = (
                '\lt'  => "less than",
                '\gt'  => "greater than",
                '\leq' => "less than or equal to",
                '\geq' => "greater than or equal to"
              );
              $words = $words{$sign};
              if ($sign eq '\lt' || $sign eq '\gt') {
                $sol[0] = "does not allow";
                $sol[1] = "parenthesis";
                $sol[2] = "infiniteopeninterval";
              } else {
                $sol[0] = "allows";
                $sol[1] = "bracket";
                $sol[2] = "infiniteclosedinterval";
              }
              if ($sign eq '\lt' || $sign eq '\leq') {
                $sol[3] = -12;
              } else {
                $sol[3] = 12;
              }
            </pg-code>
            <statement>
              <p>
                <m><var name="$left"/><var name="$sign"/><var name="$right"/></m>
              </p>
              <p>
                <var name="$gt" width="1"/>
              </p>
              <instruction>
                In interval notation.
              </instruction>
              <p>
                <var name="$interval" width="12"/>
              </p>
              <instruction>
                In set-builder notation. (If needed, type <c>inf</c> or <c>infinity</c>
                for <m>\infty</m>, <c>&gt;=</c> for <m>\geq</m>, and <c>&lt;=</c> for <m>\leq</m>.)
              </instruction>
              <p>
                <var name="$setbuilder" width="12"/>
              </p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
              <p>
                The opposite action to multiplication is division:
                <md>
                  <mrow><var name="$left"/><var name="$sign"/><var name="$right"/></mrow>
                  <mrow>\divideunder{<var name="$left"/>}{<var name="$a"/>}<var name="$sign"/>\divideunder{<var name="$right"/>}{<var name="$a"/>}</mrow>
                  <mrow><var name="$var"/> <var name="$sign"/> <var name="$c"/></mrow>
                </md>
                So in set-builder notation, the solution set is <m><var name="$setbuilder"/></m>.
              </p>
              <p>
                We can graph this by shading all numbers <var name="$words"/>
                <m><var name="$c"/></m>. Since the sign in the inequality <var name="$sol[0]"/> for
                <m><var name="$var"/></m> to equal <m><var name="$c"/></m>, we use a
                <var name="$sol[1]"/> at <m><var name="$c"/></m>.
              </p>
              <image>
                <latex-image>
                  \begin{tikzpicture}
                    \begin{axis}[numberline, xlabel={\($var\)}]
                      \addplot[$sol[2]] coordinates {($sol[3],0) ($c,0)};
                    \end{axis}
                  \end{tikzpicture}
                </latex-image>
              </image>
              <p>
                We read the graph from left to right to tell us the interval notation for the
                solution set: <m><var name="$interval"/></m>.
              </p>
            </solution>
          </webwork>
        </exercise>
        <exercise label="solve-inequality-negative-divide-by-integer">
          <webwork xml:id="webwork-solve-inequality-negative-divide-by-integer">
            <pg-macros>
              <macro-file>parserGraphTool.pl</macro-file>
            </pg-macros>
            <pg-code>
              $var = list_random('a'..'n','p'..'z','A'..'D', 'F'..'N','P'..'T','V'..'Z');
              Context()->variables->are($var => 'Real');
              $c = list_random(4,6,8,10,12);
              $a = ($c == 4) ? list_random(2,4) :
                   ($c == 6) ? list_random(2,3,6) :
                   ($c == 8) ? list_random(2,4,8) :
                   ($c == 10) ? list_random(2,5,10) :
                   list_random(2,3,4,6,12);
              $c = list_random(-$c, $c);
              $b = -$c/$a;
              $left = Formula("-$var/$a")->reduce;
              $right = Formula("$b")->reduce;
              $sign = list_random('\lt', '\gt', '\leq', '\geq');
              %interval = (
                '\lt'  => "($c, inf)",
                '\gt'  => "(-inf, $c)",
                '\leq' => "[$c, inf)",
                '\geq' => "(-inf, $c]"
              );
              Context("Interval");
              $interval = Interval($interval{$sign});
              InequalitySetBuilder::UseVerticalSuchThat();
              Context("InequalitySetBuilder-Only");
              Context()->variables->are($var => 'Real');
              %perlsign = (
                '\lt'  => ">",
                '\gt'  => "&lt;",
                '\leq' => ">=",
                '\geq' => "&lt;="
              );
              $perlsign = $perlsign{$sign};
              $setbuilder = Compute("{ $var | $var $perlsign $c}");
              $gt = GraphTool("{interval, $interval}")->with(
                availableTools => ['IntervalTool', 'IncludeExcludePointTool'],
                numberLine => 1,
                xAxisLabel => "$var",
                bBox => [ -16, 16 ],
                ticksDistanceX => 4,
                minorTicksX => 3,
                useBracketEnds => 1,
                showInStatic => 0,
                showCoordinateHints => 0,
              );
            </pg-code>
            <statement>
              <p>
                <m><var name="$left"/><var name="$sign"/><var name="$right"/></m>
              </p>
              <p>
                <var name="$gt" width="1"/>
              </p>
              <instruction>
                In interval notation.
              </instruction>
              <p>
                <var name="$interval" width="12"/>
              </p>
              <instruction>
                In set-builder notation. (If needed, type <c>inf</c> or <c>infinity</c>
                for <m>\infty</m>, <c>&gt;=</c> for <m>\geq</m>, and <c>&lt;=</c> for <m>\leq</m>.)
              </instruction>
              <p>
                <var name="$setbuilder" width="12"/>
              </p>
            </statement>
          </webwork>
        </exercise>
        <exercise label="solve-inequality-multiply-negative-integer">
          <webwork xml:id="webwork-solve-inequality-multiply-negative-integer">
            <pg-macros>
              <macro-file>parserGraphTool.pl</macro-file>
            </pg-macros>
            <pg-code>
              $var = list_random('a'..'n','p'..'z','A'..'D', 'F'..'N','P'..'T','V'..'Z');
              Context()->variables->are($var => 'Real');
              $c = non_zero_random(-6,6);
              $a = -1*random(2,20);
              $b = $a*$c;
              $left = Formula("$a $var")->reduce;
              $right = Formula("$b")->reduce;
              $sign = list_random('\lt', '\gt', '\leq', '\geq');
              %interval = (
                '\lt'  => "($c, inf)",
                '\gt'  => "(-inf, $c)",
                '\leq' => "[$c, inf)",
                '\geq' => "(-inf, $c]"
              );
              Context("Interval");
              $interval = Interval($interval{$sign});
              InequalitySetBuilder::UseVerticalSuchThat();
              Context("InequalitySetBuilder-Only");
              Context()->variables->are($var => 'Real');
              %perlsign = (
                '\lt'  => ">",
                '\gt'  => "&lt;",
                '\leq' => ">=",
                '\geq' => "&lt;="
              );
              $perlsign = $perlsign{$sign};
              $setbuilder = Compute("{ $var | $var $perlsign $c}");
              $gt = GraphTool("{interval, $interval}")->with(
                availableTools => ['IntervalTool', 'IncludeExcludePointTool'],
                numberLine => 1,
                xAxisLabel => "$var",
                bBox => [ -8, 8 ],
                ticksDistanceX => 1,
                minorTicksX => 0,
                useBracketEnds => 1,
                showInStatic => 0,
                showCoordinateHints => 0,
              );
              %oppsign = (
                '\lt'  => '\gt',
                '\gt'  => '\lt',
                '\leq' => '\geq',
                '\geq' => '\leq'
              );
              $oppsign = $oppsign{$sign};
              %words = (
                '\lt'  => "less than",
                '\gt'  => "greater than",
                '\leq' => "less than or equal to",
                '\geq' => "greater than or equal to"
              );
              $words = $words{$oppsign};
              if ($oppsign eq '\lt' || $oppsign eq '\gt') {
                $sol[0] = "does not allow";
                $sol[1] = "parenthesis";
                $sol[2] = "infiniteopeninterval";
              } else {
                $sol[0] = "allows";
                $sol[1] = "bracket";
                $sol[2] = "infiniteclosedinterval";
              }
              if ($oppsign eq '\lt' || $oppsign eq '\leq') {
                $sol[3] = -12;
              } else {
                $sol[3] = 12;
              }
            </pg-code>
            <statement>
              <p>
                <m><var name="$left"/><var name="$sign"/><var name="$right"/></m>
              </p>
              <p>
                <var name="$gt" width="1"/>
              </p>
              <instruction>
                In interval notation.
              </instruction>
              <p>
                <var name="$interval" width="12"/>
              </p>
              <instruction>
                In set-builder notation. (If needed, type <c>inf</c> or <c>infinity</c>
                for <m>\infty</m>, <c>&gt;=</c> for <m>\geq</m>, and <c>&lt;=</c> for <m>\leq</m>.)
              </instruction>
              <p>
                <var name="$setbuilder" width="12"/>
              </p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
              <p>
                The opposite action to multiplication is division. When we divide by a negative
                number, the inequality sign must change direction.
                <md>
                  <mrow><var name="$left"/><var name="$sign"/><var name="$right"/></mrow>
                  <mrow>\divideunder{<var name="$left"/>}{<var name="$a"/>}\highlight{<var name="$oppsign"/>}\divideunder{<var name="$right"/>}{<var name="$a"/>}</mrow>
                  <mrow><var name="$var"/> <var name="$oppsign"/> <var name="$c"/></mrow>
                </md>
                So in set-builder notation, the solution set is <m><var name="$setbuilder"/></m>.
              </p>
              <p>
                We can graph this by shading all numbers <var name="$words"/>
                <m><var name="$c"/></m>. Since the sign in the inequality <var name="$sol[0]"/> for
                <m><var name="$var"/></m> to equal <m><var name="$c"/></m>, we use a
                <var name="$sol[1]"/> at <m><var name="$c"/></m>.
              </p>
              <image>
                <latex-image>
                  \begin{tikzpicture}
                    \begin{axis}[numberline, xlabel={\($var\)}]
                      \addplot[$sol[2]] coordinates {($sol[3],0) ($c,0)};
                    \end{axis}
                  \end{tikzpicture}
                </latex-image>
              </image>
              <p>
                We read the graph from left to right to tell us the interval notation for the
                solution set: <m><var name="$interval"/></m>.
              </p>
            </solution>
          </webwork>
        </exercise>
      </exercisegroup>
    </subexercises>

    <subexercises>
      <title>Notation</title>
      <exercise label="write-no-solution">
        <webwork>
          <pg-code>
            Context("FiniteSolutionSets");
            $solution = String("no real solutions")->cmp(typeMatch => Formula("{1}"));
          </pg-code>
          <statement>
            <p>
              What is one valid way to communicate that there are no solutions to an equation?
              (There are several correct answers.)
            </p>
            <p>
              <var name="$solution" width="16"/>
            </p>
          </statement>
        </webwork>
      </exercise>
      <exercise label="write-all-numbers-are-solutions">
        <webwork>
          <pg-code>
            Context("FiniteSolutionSets");
            $solution = OneOf(Compute("R"), String("infinitely many solutions"))->cmp(typeMatch => Formula("{1}"));
          </pg-code>
          <statement>
            <p>
              What is one valid way to communicate that all real numbers are solutions to an equation?
              (There are several correct answers.)
            </p>
            <p>
              <var name="$solution" width="16"/>
            </p>
          </statement>
        </webwork>
      </exercise>
    </subexercises>

